title: Digital Transformation Tech Talk 19 webinar October 2024
description:
The Department of Health and Aged Care’s continuing webinar series centres on ways to build a better-connected, sustainable and modern aged care IT network.

Our Tech Talk 19 shared updates following recent aged care reform announcements. Presenters also gave updates on digital transformation work including Support at Home, and the Business to Government (B2G) project.

title: Shingles vaccination – Uncle Rod
description:
Uncle Rod wants mob aged 50 and over to know that they could be eligible for free shingles vaccination. He explains how much shingles can affect you, both physically and mentally.

The good news is there’s a safe and effective shingles vaccine – free under the National Immunisation Program for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people 50 years or older.

title: New Aged Care Infection Prevention and Control Guide – Webinar recording
description:
This webinar was created to help attendees understand how the new Aged Care Infection Prevention and Control (IPC) Guide can be used to: 
• apply basic principles of infection prevention and control in aged care  
• minimise the risk of infection for older people and the workforce, by taking a risk-based approach 
• meet the Aged Care Quality Standards 
• develop local policies and procedures to support IPC within your organisation.

It also allowed attendees to participate in Q&A about the new guide.

Presenters were:
• (Chair) Rhiannon Box, Assistant Secretary, Emergency Preparedness & Response, Department of Health and Aged Care
• (Presenter) Professor Alison McMillan, Chief Nursing and Midwifery Officer, Department of Health and Aged Care
• (Presenter) Loren deVries, Senior Practitioner, Qualified Nurse Practitioner Aged Care, Aged Care Quality and Safety Commission
• (Presenter) Professor Peter Collignon, Senior Medical Advisor for the Australian Commission on Safety
 
00:00 
Welcome and overview by Chair Rhiannon Box, Assistant Secretary, Emergency Preparedness & Response, Department of Health and Aged Care  

4:05
Professor Peter Collignon, Senior Medical Advisor for the Australian Commission on Safety presenting on key components of the new IPC Guide and how the sector can use this resource.

19:40 Loren deVries, Senior Practitioner, Qualified Nurse Practitioner Aged Care, Aged Care Quality and Safety Commission presenting on how the new IPC guide can assist aged care providers in meeting their obligations under the new Aged Care Act.

39:28
Professor Alison McMillan, Chief Nursing and Midwifery Officer, Department of Health and Aged Care presenting on the differences between the new IPC guide and the Communicable Diseases Network of Australia National Guideline for the Prevention, Control and Public Health Management of Outbreaks of Acute Respiratory Infection in Residential Aged Care Homes.

48:30 
Q&A

58:39
End

title: World Arthritis Day - Hear from Chief Nursing and Midwifery Officer, Professor Alison McMillan
description:
🎥 Hear from Prof. Alison McMillan as she shares tips on managing arthritis effectively ahead of World Arthritis Day tomorrow.

🦴 Arthritis can cause joint pain, swelling, and stiffness. 

Early treatment and staying active with low-impact exercises like walking, swimming, and yoga can help manage symptoms.

For more information, resources, and support, visit 💻 https://arthritisaustralia.com.au/get-support/resources/

title: Eye Health - Hear from Chief Nursing and Midwifery Officer, Professor Alison McMillan
description:
🎥 Hear from Prof. Alison McMillan on World Sight Day as she shares essential tips on maintaining eye health.

👀 Spending long hours on devices can strain your eyes. Follow the 20-20-20 rule: every 20 minutes, take a 20-second break and look at something 20 feet away. 

🕶️ Good lighting and wearing sunglasses with UV protection are also important.

For more information, resources and support, visit 🖥️ https://visionaustralia.org/

title: Introducing the Aged Care Council of Elders
description: The Aged Care Council of Elders are a group of older people from diverse backgrounds with lived experiences of ageing and aged care. The council help to improve the aged care system by informing older people about the changes to aged care, and providing advice to the Australian Government about aged care reform and ageing well. Find out more at www.health.gov.au/committees-and-groups/aged-care-council-of-elders

title: Shield yourself from shingles – What is shingles?
description:
If you’ve had chickenpox as a kid, you can get shingles as an adult.
It can be really nasty; especially if you are over 50 or if your immune system is weak.
The good news is there’s a safe and effective shingles vaccine – free under the National Immunisation Program for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people 50 years or older.

title: Experiencing the Aged Care Nursing Clinical Placements Program
description:
Hear from nursing students participating in the Aged Care Nursing Clinical Placements Program talk about their reflections and experiences of clinical placements in the aged care sector. 

The program supports nursing students with positive, high-quality clinical placements in the care and support sector (aged care, veterans’ care, and disability). During their placement, students can practice advanced clinical skills, learn about gerontological nursing, and see the complexity of care and depth of knowledge required to be an aged care nurse, whilst receiving specialist support by trained clinical facilitators.

title: Improving aged care homes through design
description:
This webinar video will support the aged care sector to understand how to adopt the new National Aged Care Design Principles and Guidelines. You will hear how the principles and guidelines can improve aged care design and benefit those living and working there.

The webinar was presented on Thursday, August 15 2024 2:00 pm AEST to 3:00pm AEST

Presenters:
• Chair – Marianne Madden, Acting Assistant Secretary, Dementia, Diversity and Design Branch, Department of Health and Aged Care.  
• Presenter – Naomi Wilkins, Director, Design and Dementia Support Section, Department of Health and Aged Care
• Presenter – Nick Seemann, Managing Director, Constructive Dialogue Architects and Dementia Training Australia, a lead author of the Principles and Guidelines
• Presenter – Liz Fuggle, Associate, Constructive Dialogue Architects and Dementia Training Australia, a lead author of the Principles and Guidelines
• Presenter – Angela Raguz, General Manager, Residential Care and Dementia Centre, HammondCare

00:00 Welcome and introduction, Marianne Madden, Acting Assistant Secretary, Dementia, Diversity and Design Branch, DoHAC

02:35 Overview and next steps, Naomi Wilkins, Director, Design and Dementia Support Section, DoHAC

05:20 Overview of Principles and Guidelines, Nick Seemann, Managing Director, Constructive Dialogue Architects and Dementia Training Australia and Liz Fuggle, associate, Constructive Dialogue Architects and Dementia Training Australia

25:12 What good aged care design looks like and HammondCare’s experience, Angela Raguz, General Manager, Residential Care and Dementia Centre, HammondCare

43:14 Next steps from here, support for aged care providers, Naomi Wilkins, Director, Design and Dementia Support Section, DoHAC

47:45 Audience Q&A with all presenters.

title: Get behind it! Community Roadshow for the National Bowel Cancer Screening Program
description:
It’s time to Get behind it! 
The National Bowel Cancer Screening Program is available every two years to 45-74 year old Australians yet not enough of those eligible are completing it. That’s why we’re hitting the road to bring awareness to the program that saves lives. When found early, over 90% of bowel cancers can be successfully treated. Do the test, it’s free, easy and could save your life.

title: How to do the free test – National Bowel Cancer Screening Program
description:
Eligible Australians aged 45 to 74 can do the free National Bowel Cancer Screening Program test. Bowel cancer screening can save your life, so do your test when you receive it in the mail. When found early, nine out of ten cases can be treated successfully.
 
For more information on bowel screening, visit www.health.gov.au/nbcsp.

title: Keep at Quitting the Vapes - Kedea’s Story
description:
Kedea recently quit the vapes to help improve her physical and mental wellbeing.  It took a few attempts, and she encountered setbacks along the way, but eventually Kedea was able to quit the vapes for good.

Quitting the vapes might take several tries. You can learn something from every quit attempt, and each try will bring you closer to giving up for good. 

Find tools and support to quit at http://www.health.gov.au/GiveUpForGood

title: Aged care financial reporting webinar – July 2024
description:
This webinar supported aged care providers with their regulatory reporting requirements. It highlighted some key changes to upcoming Quarterly Financial Report and the Aged Care Financial Report 2023–24 data collections. 

0:00 Welcome and overview by Chair, Jessica Evans, Assistant Secretary, Market Intelligence Branch, Department of Health and Aged Care.

03:07 Jessica Evans, Assistant Secretary, Market Intelligence Branch, Department of Health and Aged Care presenting on recent and upcoming publications.

06:45 Kate Stewart, Director, Financial Reporting Operations Section, Department of Health and Aged Care presenting on Dollars Going to Care and recent and upcoming publications.

12:03 Jarrod Bowd, Director, Financial Reporting and Analysis Section, Department of Health and Aged Care presenting on data quality assurance and upcoming changes in the Quarterly Financial Report.

17:36 Aden Pulford, Acting Director, Residential Care Funding Reform, Department of Health and Aged Care presenting on care time reporting in the Quarterly Financial Report.

19:44 Jarrod Bowd, Director, Financial Reporting and Analysis Section, Department of Health and Aged Care presenting on the Quarterly Financial Report.

25:11 Kate Stewart, Director, Financial Reporting Operations Section, Department of Health and Aged Care presenting on the Quarterly Financial Report user experience survey.

28:13 Jarrod Bowd, Director, Financial Reporting and Analysis Section, Department of Health and Aged Care presenting on the 2023-24 Aged Care Financial Report.

title: Meet Professor John McCallum - member of the Aged Care Council of Elders
description: Professor John McCallum is a member of the Aged Care Council of Elders. John lives in Canberra and is an advocate for ageing well and aged care issues. He is passionate about older people living well while maintaining quality of life. Learn more about the Aged Care Council of Elders at: www.health.gov.au/committees-and-groups/aged-care-council-of-elders

title: Lucy’s story – part three
description:
Children can become seriously ill from influenza and in some cases, it can be fatal.

This was the case for 2-year-old Lucy, who suffered serious complications from influenza.

In this video, her mother Rhiannon shares their family’s experience with influenza, to warn other parents about the serious risks of flu in young children.

Protect your child by getting them vaccinated – free under the National Immunisation Program for children 6 months to under 5 years.

title: Delivering high quality, person-centred palliative care in aged care
description:
This webinar was for anyone working in aged care. Leading palliative care experts talked about education and training opportunities to help you deliver high quality, person-centred palliative care. 

0:00 Welcome, introductions and overview by Co-chair, Nicole Fitzgerald, Assistant Secretary, Newborn Screening and Palliative Care Branch, Department of Health and Aged Care 
06:03 Presentation by Co-chair, Ingrid Leonard, Assistant Secretary, Choice and Transparency Branch, Department of Health and Aged Care
13:29 Presentation by Distinguished Professor Patsy Yates, AM, PhD, RN, FACN, FAAN, Executive Dean of the Faculty of Health at Queensland University of Technology (QUT) and Director for Queensland Health’s Centre for Palliative Care Research
19:10 Presentation by Fiona McLeod, Nurse Educator, Program of Experience in the Palliative Approach (PEPA)
26:13 Presentation by Professor Claire Johnson, Director, Palliative Aged Care Outcomes Program (PACOP), Professorial Fellow, Palliative Care Outcomes Collaboration (PCOC)
41:13 Presentation by Rebecca Moore, Project Coordinator, End of Life Directions for Aged Care (ELDAC) 
48:42 Q&A
1:06:26 End

Presenters were: 
• Nicole Fitzgerald, Assistant Secretary, Newborn Screening and Palliative Care Branch, Department of Health and Aged Care (Co-chair)
• Ingrid Leonard, Assistant Secretary, Choice and Transparency Branch, Department of Health and Aged Care (Co-chair)
• Distinguished Professor Patsy Yates, AM, PhD, RN, FACN, FAAN, Executive Dean of the Faculty of Health at Queensland University of Technology (QUT) and Director for Queensland Health’s Centre for Palliative Care Research
• Fiona McLeod, Nurse Educator, Program of Experience in the Palliative Approach (PEPA)
• Rebecca Moore, Project Coordinator, End of Life Directions for Aged Care (ELDAC) 
• Professor Claire Johnson, Director, Palliative Aged Care Outcomes Program (PACOP), Professorial Fellow, Palliative Care Outcomes Collaboration (PCOC)

title: Shield yourself from shingles – Where to get the shingles vaccine
description:
Shingles is a viral infection that can be really nasty; especially if you’re over 50 or if your immune system is weak. 

Dr Richard Mills and Registered Nurse and Bundjalung woman Trina Scott encourage people to shield themselves from shingles with a vaccine – free for eligible people under the National Immunisation Program (NIP). 

Talk with your health professional about your eligibility today.

title: Medicare Urgent Care Clinics – Bhavana’s story (Vietnamese)
description:
Bhavana shares her experience of visiting a Medicare Urgent Care Clinic (Medicare UCCs) when her eye started to sting after hours. Medicare UCCs are located across Australia, making it easier to access care for urgent, but not life-threatening, illnesses and injuries.

Find your nearest Medicare Urgent Care Clinic at health.gov.au/MedicareUCC

title: Digital Transformation Tech Talk Webinar - 21 May 2024
description:
An ongoing webinar series for the aged care sector focused on creating a better-connected, sustainable and modern aged care IT network. 

This Digital Transformation Tech Talk webinar took place during National Palliative Care Week, giving our usual update on all things digital transformation, with a live Q&A at the end of the session. 

See our updates to the Business to Government (B2G) Gateway (which is delivering Application Programming Interfaces – APIs – to make it easier for providers to exchange information with government systems)

Hear about data standardisation for the aged care sector and the ELDAC dashboard, which supports quality palliative and end-of-life care.

title: True or Gammon – STIs with Janty and Jecinta
description: Deadly comedian Janty Blair yarns with Aboriginal Health Practitioner, Jecinta from Darwin, NT. In ‘True or Gammon’ style, they shed light on some myths about STIs. Tip: #1 tip is always practice safe sex. Use a condom and lube. It’s kind of like the shield that protects you both. There’s no shame for women to carry condoms. A condom can fit almost 4 litres of water – TRUE. Any fulla telling you their condom won’t fit - they’re GAMMON.

description:
Demonstrates how you can engage with you participation in the National Cervical Screening Program, including the last time you screened, when you’re next due to screen, and notifications if you’re overdue or if there are any recommendations following your last screening results.

You can also:

• defer your next screening date,
• cease correspondence, and
• update your communication preferences.

title: Participant Portal – Introduction
description:
Welcome to the walk-through guide for the Participant Portal which allows participants of the National Bowel Cancer Screening Program, and the National Cervical Screening Program to:
1. Update personal details and communication preferences
2. Manage participation in the screening programs, including deferring your next screening date
3. View screening status and when you’re next due to screen
4. Nominate a healthcare provider for each screening program
5. View previous screening-program related messages, and
6. Request a free replacement bowel screening program home test kit, if it is lost, damaged or expired.

title: New Aged Care Act Q&A session
description:
This webinar recording is a Q&A session about the draft new Aged Care Act, which was available for consultation from 14 December 2023 to 8 March 2024. The panel answered questions from the audience. 
 
Presenters are: 
• Amy Laffan, First Assistant Secretary, Quality & Assurance Division.
• Mel Metz, Assistant Secretary, Legislative Reform Branch.
• Katie Holm, Assistant Secretary, Strengthening Providers Branch.
• Simon Christopher, Acting Assistant Secretary, Harmonisation and Regulatory Strategy Branch.

14:00 Welcome, Acknowledgement of Country and Overview by Chair, Amy Laffan, First Assistant Secretary, Quality and Assurance Division, Aging and Aged Care Group

14:05 Presenters were introduced; Mel Metz, Assistant Secretary, Legislative Reform Branch, Katie Holm, Assistant Secretary, Strengthening Providers Branch and Simon Christopher, Acting Assistant Secretary, Harmonisation and Regulatory Strategy Branch.

14:10 Presenters addressed the following themes:
* Exposure draft of the Bill for the new Aged Care Act
* Readiness and transition support
* Regulatory Framework
* Regulatory Approach

14:30 Presenters responded to questions from attendees throughout the session.

15:00 Conclusion and end of session

title: Introducing the Interim First Nations Aged Care Commissioner - Andrea Kelly
description:
Introducing the Interim First Nations Aged Care Commissioner, Andrea Kelly.

Andrea is a proud Warumungu and Larrakia woman who is passionate about achieving positive change for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.

She’s consulting with First Nations older people, families, communities and stakeholders to inform the role of the permanent Commissioner and help improve care for First Nations older people across the aged care system. 

To share your ideas, get in touch at  interimFNACCconsultations@health.gov.au or by visiting health.gov.au/contacts/interim-first-nations-aged-care-commissioner

title: Dedication Ceremony & unveiling of the National Site of Recognition for Thalidomide Survivors
description:
A National Site of Recognition for Thalidomide Survivors and their Families was established by the Australian Government to acknowledge the thalidomide tragedy in Australia. The site honours the pain and suffering experienced by thalidomide survivors, the memory of those who died prematurely, as well as the impact on their loved ones.

In November 2023, a Dedication Ceremony took place together with the unveiling of the National Site of Recognition in Canberra. The official dedication was delivered by the Minister for Health and Aged Care, the Hon Mark Butler MP. Personal reflections were also provided by thalidomide survivors and advocates. 

Date: 30 November 2023
Location: Kings Park, Canberra, Australia

title: Draft new Aged Care Act consultation – Q&A panel discussion
description:
This webinar is an interactive discussion about the final draft of the new Aged Care Act which is currently available for consultation until 16 February 2024.

0:00 Welcome and introduction – Amy Laffan
2:34 Consultation on the new Aged Care Act exposure draft
3:23 Q&A panel discussion
59:42 End 

Presenters are: 
• Amy Laffan, First Assistant Secretary, Quality & Assurance Division 
• Mel Metz, Assistant Secretary, Legislative Reform Branch 
• Caroline Turnour, Assistant Secretary, Harmonisation & Regulatory Strategy Branch 
• Janet Anderson, Aged Care Quality and Safety Commissioner.

title: New Aged Care Act and Support at Home program update
description:
This webinar provides updates on: the development of the new Aged Care Act, a new model for regulating aged care, the strengthened Aged Care Quality Standards, and in-home aged care reforms, including the new Support at Home program. It also includes a live question-and-answer session.

0:00 Welcome and introduction
3:20 New Aged Care Act – Mel Metz
27:53 New Aged Care Act next step 
29:40 Provider registration categories – Simon Christopher
35:28 Transition and deeming arrangements
37:47 The strengthened Aged Care Quality Standards – Ingrid Leonard
43:04 Support at Home staging and implementation – Nick Morgan
47:54 Why are we staging the implementation
49:23 What will in home aged care look like in July 2025
55:28 What will in home aged care look like post July 2027
56:25 Assessment classification and funding arrangements
1:06 Support at home next steps
1:08 Q&A 
1:26 End 

Presenters are: 
• Amy Laffan, First Assistant Secretary, Quality and Assurance Division
• Mel Metz, Assistant Secretary, Legislative Reform Branch 
• Simon Christopher, Director, Harmonisation and  Regulatory Strategy Branch 
• Ingrid Leonard, Assistant Secretary, Choice and Transparency Branch 
• Nick Morgan, Assistant Secretary, Support at Home Reform Branch

title: Understanding the difference between routine, urgent and emergency care - animation
description:
Learn the difference between routine, urgent and emergency care. To find a Medicare Urgent Care Clinic near you, visit health.gov.au/MedicareUCC.

Full transcript:
Medicare Urgent Care Clinics are located across Australia and make it easier to access bulk-billed, urgent health care.
They’re open early and late every day, and you don't need an appointment or referral.
Urgent care is when you need medical attention for an illness or injury that can’t wait for a regular appointment with a GP, but doesn’t require care for emergency or life-threatening illnesses or injuries.
Things that may need urgent medical care include minor fractures, sprains, minor infections; respiratory illnesses; mild burns; severe stomach pains; or
urinary tract infections.
Emergency or life-threatening illnesses or injuries require immediate medical attention by an emergency department or hospital.
For example, things like chest pain, breathing difficulties, severe burns, poisoning, loss of feeling, and seizures.
Your local GP is your first point of contact for routine and preventative health care. Some GPs also offer same day appointments.
To find your nearest Medicare Urgent Care Clinic, visit health.gov.au/MedicareUCC

title: When should you visit a Medicare Urgent Care Clinic? - animation
description:
Information to help you decide where to go when you have an illness or injury. To find a Medicare Urgent Care Clinic near you, visit health.gov.au/MedicareUCC.

Full transcript:
Medicare Urgent Care Clinics are located across Australia and make it easier to access care for urgent, but not life-threatening, illnesses and injuries.
But how do you know what’s urgent and what’s not?
If you have an injury or illness that needs medical attention, there are three questions you can ask yourself before deciding where to go for help.
• Is it life-threatening and do I need emergency care?
• Is it something a GP or nurse can treat?
• Can it wait until I can get an appointment to see my local GP?
If it’s not an emergency but you can’t wait for a regular appointment with your GP … that’s a case for a Medicare Urgent Care Clinic.
Medicare Urgent Care Clinics are open early and late every day, services are bulk billed and you don't need an appointment or referral.
To find your nearest Medicare Urgent Care Clinic, visit health.gov.au/MedicareUCC

title: What do Medicare Urgent Care Clinics offer? - animation
description:
Medicare UCCs are located across Australia and provide urgent, bulk billed health care. To find a Medicare Urgent Care Clinic near you, visit health.gov.au/MedicareUCC.

Full transcript:
Medicare Urgent Care Clinics are located across Australia and make it easier to access care for urgent, but not life-threatening, illnesses and injuries.
Going to a Medicare Urgent Care Clinic means you don’t have to wait at your local emergency department.
They are:
• Bulk billed, so bring your Medicare card
• Walk-in, so you don’t need an appointment or referral
• Open early and late every day
• Staffed by GPs and nurses.
Visit your local Medicare Urgent Care Clinic if you have an illness or injury that can’t wait for a regular appointment with a GP, but doesn’t require a trip to
hospital.
If you or a loved one has a life-threatening injury or illness, call triple zero or go straight to your nearest emergency department.
To find your nearest Medicare Urgent Care Clinic, visit health.gov.au/MedicareUCC

description:

title: SSI Home Care Workforce Support Program
description:
Embark on a meaningful career and make a difference with every door you open. Join the SSI Home Care Workforce Support Program (HCWSP).
SSI is delivering the government-funded Home Care Workforce Support Program (HCWSP) in New South Wales (NSW) and the ACT to help Australia’s seniors enjoy a safe and independent life at home.
The program aims to grow, upskill, train and support an aged care workforce that delivers safe, high-quality care that puts seniors first.
The program is free and open to anyone who wants to build a meaningful career supporting seniors.

title: Care Community Launch
description:
Care Community is The Home Care Workforce Support Program in Western Australia. It is a project by the Australian Government to help connect people with jobs in aged home care.

North Metropolitan TAFE is proud to lead the Home Care Workforce Support Program in Western Australia, in partnership with South Metropolitan TAFE. Their goal is to grow and upskill home care workers, including an increase in diversity of gender, culture, language, age and regionally located staff.

description:
An ongoing webinar series for the aged care sector focused on creating a better-connected, sustainable and modern aged care IT network. 

In this webinar we shared an update on the Department of Health and Aged Care's digital strategy, we heard from the Australian Digital Health Agency (ADHA), and updated on some key digital transformation initiatives (specifically, Quarterly Financial Reports (QFR) and Business to Government (B2G) exchange capabilities).

title: Aged Care Volunteer Visitors Scheme (ACVVS)
description:
In this webinar we gave an overview of the Aged Care Volunteer Visitors Scheme (ACVVS) for Home Care Package providers and residential care providers. 
 
0:00 Welcome and introduction
1:34 What is ACVVS

title: Childhood Immunisation – Health Worker Irene talks about how getting immunised can protect children
description:
Advanced Health Worker Irene Nicholls from Mackay in Central Queensland discusses how immunisation protects children.

Transcript:
Why are childhood immunisations so important?
Everyone wants their bubbies and littlies not to get sick.
One way we can all help them stay healthy is with free childhood immunisations.
Different immunisations are recommended between birth and age 4 that will help protect your kids from lots of serious diseases.

How do immunisations help keep them healthy?
Immunisation works like a shield protecting them against diseases. These diseases can be really dangerous and make kids and little ones very sick or cause long-term health problems or even death.

How does it help the rest of the community?
If a child is immunised there’s less of a chance of them getting very sick. And spreading the diseases to others.
When lots of people get vaccinated it helps protect the whole community which is really important, as it can help protect bubbas who are too young, and others in our communities who are too sick to be vaccinated themselves.

I’m worried about what I’m giving to my kids.
It’s completely natural to be worried about anything you’re giving to your kids.
But vaccines in Australia have been carefully tested, and over generations serious diseases like polio and diphtheria have almost completely disappeared here, thanks to lots of us getting vaccinated.

I’ve heard it’s important that kids get their immunisations on time. What do I do if I’ve missed one?
It’s important to follow the Childhood Immunisation Schedule.
This tells you what vaccines your child needs and when.
But if your little one has missed something, it’s easy to catch up.
Don’t worry, just talk to your doctor or health worker, and we’ll help you get your kids’ immunisations up to date.

Will it hurt? What do I do if my kids are scared?
It’s natural for kids to be a bit nervous at immunisation time, but we can help distract them and keep them feeling okay.
Immunisations may hurt a tiny bit, like a pin prick, but it happens fast. And if they get a reaction, it’s usually mild and doesn’t last too long.

What if I have more questions?
You can always talk with parents and Elders about their own vaccination experiences and doctors and health workers understand that you might have questions and we’re here to help answer them, no matter how big or small.
It’s important to yarn so we can help keep the next generation of us mob safe.
Have a yarn to your doctor or health worker about free routine childhood immunisation or visit health.gov.au/childhoodimmunisation for more information.
It’s just one more way we keep our little ones safe.

title: Dr Mark Wenitong explains how to use a nasal rapid antigen test (RAT)
description:
In this video, Dr Mark Wenitong explains how to use a nasal rapid antigen test (RAT).

Transcript:
Hi, I’m Dr Mark Wenitong, and I want to show all you Mob the right way to use a Rapid Antigen Test – or RAT Test – to check to see if you have COVID-19.

If you’ve been in contact with someone who has COVID-19, or you have symptoms like fever or cough, it’s good to test to see if you have COVID.

A RAT can be an easy way to see whether or not you have COVID. 

And you can do the test yourself without a doctor, in the comfort of your own home,  and get the results in just 10 to 20 minutes.

You can buy RATs from your local pharmacy, supermarket and lots of other retail stores, as well as online. 

You can also check on your state or territory health department website.

There are a few different types of RAT kits available – but the three most common are one that tests the spit from your mouth, one that you suck like a lollipop, and one that takes a sample from your nose. 

Remember, no matter what test you have, before you start, wash your hands 
and make sure you have a watch or timer handy.

If you’re using a RAT that takes a sample from your nose, inside your kit you’ll find a strip that will show you if you have COVID-19 or not, a long stick with 1 soft end, atube with lid and a small pack with liquid called the buffer.

Some kits also have a stand and a torch.

First, make sure you have the tube the right way up.

Your test kit might come with a stand to help. Be careful not to let the tube fall over.

Open a pack with a buffer and pour it into the tube, making sure to not get any on your skin or eyes.   
Take the stick out of the packet, making sure you don’t touch the soft part of the stick.

Put the soft part up your nose, all the way up until it you feel it touch the back of your nose.

Keep moving the stick around. 

Use the soft end of the same stick and do the other side of your nose.

When you’re done put the stick into the tube and stir it 10 times.

Then, gently squeeze the sides of the tube together 10 times before taking the stick out. Put the cap tightly on the tube. 

Put the cap tightly on the tube.

Get the strip that will show you if you have COVID-19. 

Squeeze three or four drops from the tube onto the circle at the bottom 

and set your timer for 10, 15 or 20 minutes, depending on what your kit says

And you wait.

No matter what type of test you use, once your timer is up, check the strip to see what it says. 

Make sure you do it straight away, as it can be inaccurate if you leave it too long. One RAT even has a torch to help you read the strip.

If you see a line next to the C, you don’t have COVID-19.

If you see a line next to the C and the T, you are positive for COVID-19.

If you only see one line next to the letter T, or no lines at all, your test didn’t work and you’ll need to do another test.

If you’re worried about your symptoms, or if you have other health conditions call the National Coronavirus Helpline or speak to your healthcare worker.

So remember, if you need to test yourself for COVID-19, get a RAT. It’s easy and will help keep all us Mob safe.

If you need to know more, have a yarn with your local healthcare worker or visit health.gov.au.

title: Refer patients to My Aged Care easily and securely using GP e-Referrals
description:
You can now refer your patients for assessment for Australian Government-subsidised aged care services directly from your practice management system using HealthLink e-Referral.

More than 2,000 Australian practices are already using e-Referral. e-Referral is intuitive, easy to use and accessible through a patient’s electronic medical record (EMR) by selecting ‘My Aged Care Referral’ from the HealthLink referred services tab.

Patient information is pre-populated in the form, saving you time on manual data entry and reducing the risk of errors. It’s then sent securely and in real-time directly from your EMR to My Aged Care for assessment.

For more information on My Aged Care, visit the My Aged Care website: https://www.myagedcare.gov.au/health-professionals 
For more information on e-Referrals, visit the HealthLink website: https://au.healthlink.net/products/smart-forms/my-aged-care/

title: A New Model for Regulating Aged Care
description:
We’re developing a new model for regulating aged care as part of the changes to improve the quality and safety of aged care in Australia. We hosted this webinar to share the details and seek your views on the proposed changes.

0:00 Welcome and introduction to the A New Model for Regulating Aged Care 
3:31 What is regulation
5:02 Why do we need a new regulatory model?
5:08 Raising the quality of aged care
8:54 Universal provider registration and re-registration
10:45 Proposed provider registration categories
14:20 A system that is easier to access and navigate
15:23 Building provider capability
16:43 Enhanced complaints and feedback mechanisms
18:52 A strong regulator
20:39 Transitioning to the new model
22:54 How to provide feedback
23:25 Update on legislative feedback
28:40 Whistle-blower protections: What did the Royal Commission say?
34:14 Q&A 
58:50 End 

Presenters are: 
Caroline Turnour, Assistant Secretary, Harmonisation and Assurance Branch 
Mel Metz, Assistant Secretary, Legislative Reform Branch

title: Breast Cancer Screening
description:
There was no sign Julie had breast cancer. 
 
While regular self-examination is important, a mammogram every 2 years ⏰ is the best way to detect breast cancer early. A mammogram can detect cancer smaller than a grain of rice.
 
The BreastScreen Australia program provides free mammograms every 2 years for women aged 40 and over. If you’re due for your regular screening, call 📞 13 20 50 to book your appointment. It could save your life.

title: How to use your My Aged Care Online Account
description:
This video guides you through how to use your Online Account, if you are a My Aged Care client or support someone who is.

In your Online Account, you can see if you have been approved for care, update your contact details, check the progress of your Home Care Package, appoint a support person, print out referrals for services, and more.

This video will show you what you can see and do in each section within the Online Account, as well as how to link your myGov account to My Aged Care.

https://www.myagedcare.gov.au/access-your-online-account

title: Exemption process for 24/7 registered nurse responsibility – information for eligible providers
description:
This video provides information about the 24/7 registered nurse responsibility. This includes:
• the criteria for an exemption from the responsibility, including alternative clinical care arrangements an approved provider must have in place to ensure the clinical care needs of residents at the facility will be met at all times
• how to apply for the exemption and how an application will be assessed
• the role of the Aged Care Quality and Safety Commission in relation to the exemption process and regulating the 24/7 registered nurse responsibility
• reporting obligations for the 24/7 registered nurse responsibility.

title: About the NCSR’s Participant Portal
description:
The National Cancer Screening Register now has an online self-service Participant Portal. The Participant Portal provides a way for cancer screening program participants to manage their participation in the National Cervical Screening Program and National Bowel Cancer Screening Program.

Transcript:
The National Cancer Screening Register supports the Australian Government’s National Bowel Cancer Screening Program and the National Cervical Screening Program. Regular screening is one of the most effective ways to detect early signs of cancer. In most cases, early detection of cancer increases the chances of successful treatment.
The National Cancer Screening Register holds a single electronic record for the people participating in the cervical and bowel screening programs. The Register sends participants invitations and reminders to screen. An online self-service Participant Portal has been introduced to make it easier for participants to use the Register.
The Participant Portal allows you to:
• Update your personal details,
• Manage your participation in the bowel or cervical screening programs,
• View your screening status, including when you are next due to screen,
• View previous screening correspondence,
• Nominate a healthcare provider for your screening-related healthcare matters, like where your results will be sent, and
• Request a bowel test kit – this will be posted to you and can be done at home.
You can securely access the Participant Portal via your myGov account. myGov is a simple and secure way to access a range of online government services. You can create a myGov account at my.gov.au.
For more information on the Register and the Participant Portal, visit NCSR.gov.au

title: Kế hoạch Hành động Toàn quốc về chứng Sa sút Trí tuệ (National Dementia Action Plan) - Vietnamese
description:
Trong suốt cuộc đời, hầu như tất cả chúng ta sẽ bị ảnh hưởng bởi chứng sa sút trí tuệ theo cách này hay cách khác. 

Cho dù đó là qua một người thân yêu hay chính chúng ta bị, không ai phải trải qua hành trình của chứng sa sút trí tuệ một mình. 

Đó là lý do tại sao việc quý vị đóng góp ý kiến là điều quan trọng trong Kế hoạch Hành động Toàn quốc về chứng Sa sút Trí tuệ.

title: Plan Nacional de Acción contra la Demencia (National Dementia Action Plan) - Spanish
description:
A lo largo de nuestra vida, casi todos nos veremos afectados por la demencia de una u otra manera. 

Ya sea a través de un ser querido o viviendo con ella nosotros mismos, nadie debería tener que recorrer solo el camino de la demencia. 

Por eso es importante que se exprese en el Plan Nacional de Acción contra la Demencia.

Trabajamos para completar el Plan de Acción Nacional contra la Demencia a mediados de 2023 y por eso necesitamos tu aportación antes del 31 de enero.

Czy to poprzez ukochaną osobę, czy żyjąc z tym samemu, nikt nie powinien iść samotnie w podróż z demencją. 
Dlatego ważne jest, aby mieć swoje zdanie w Krajowym Planie Działań na Rzecz Demencji.

title: National Dementia Action Plan
description:
About the National Dementia Action Plan
The National Dementia Action Plan is a 10-year initiative between the Australian Government and state and territory governments.
We want Australians to understand dementia and for people living with dementia and their carers to have the best quality of life possible.
We want to know what’s important to you. With your input, the Australian Government will work with states and territories to agree actions to:
• Improve dementia diagnosis
• Improve treatment and support
• Build knowledge in our workforce
• Better support carers and families
• Increase and use new research on risk reduction and treatment
Tell us what you think at 💻 consultations.health.gov.au or call 📞 1800 565 789 (TIS) 131 450.
We are finalising the National Dementia Action Plan in 2023 and so we need your input by January 31st.

title: Webinar: Upcoming changes to specialisation verification
description:
This is a video recording of a webinar held on 11 October 2022. It provides the aged care sector an update on upcoming application process improvements, as well as the benefits for older people and providers in verifying specialisation claims.

This webinar covered the Specialisation Verification Framework and upcoming application process improvements, including the:
• new online application process for verifying specialisation claims via the My Aged Care (MAC) service and support portal
• intent and scope of the MAC Specialisation Verification initiative and accompanying Framework
• benefits for older people and providers in verifying specialisation claims
• appearance of verified specialisations on MAC versus unverified specialisations
• timeline for removing unverified claims from provider profiles on MAC (early-2023)
• opportunity for providers or representatives of diverse needs groups to ask questions.

Presenters:
• Robert Day – Assistant Secretary, Department of Health and Aged Care
• Isolde Kauffman – Director, Department of Health and Aged Care
• Representatives from the Independent assessor – Australian Healthcare Associates

title: Attracting Workers to Aged Care webinar
description:
On 14 September, over 350 people attended the first webinar of the Employer Engagement Series. This webinar covered employment programs and supports available to residential aged care and home care providers to help attract an aged care workforce. 

Presenters
• Emma Gleeson – Department of Health and Aged Care
• Jane Watts – Department of Employment and Workplace Relations
Representatives also presented from:  
• Price Waterhouse Coopers
• Council on the Ageing (COTA) Queensland Consortia Skills Hub
Agenda
The following topics were covered. 
• Workforce Advisory Service https://www.pwc.com.au/health/aged-care-workforce-advisory.html
• Aged Care Registered Nurses’ Payment https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/aged-care-registered-nurses-payment-to-reward-clinical-skills-and-leadership
• Home Care Workforce Support Program https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/home-care-workforce-support-program
• Workforce Australia – tailored supports and local employment facilitators https://www.workforceaustralia.gov.au/businesses/jobs/
If you have any questions, please email AgedCareWorkforceReform@Health.gov.au
Providers are encouraged to reach out to their local state or territory office for support at ACWorkforceChampion@health.gov.au

title: Webinar: Australian National Aged Care Classification (AN-ACC) update
description:
This is a video recording of a webinar held on 30 August 2022. It provides the aged care sector with updates on the Australian National Aged Care Classification (AN-ACC) funding model, to help with preparation and transition activities in the lead up to commencement of AN-ACC on 1 October 2022.

This webinar covered key AN-ACC topics, including:
• default classifications
• reclassification changes
• Base Care Tariff verification process
• Transition Fund eligibility
• care minutes definitions
• key functions available on the AN-ACC ICT systems (Health and Services Australia portals)
• provider readiness for go-live on 1 October 2022.

Presenters:
• Mark Richardson – Assistant Secretary, Residential Care Funding Reform Branch, Department of Health and Aged Care
• Robert Montefiore-Gardner, Therese Richards, Claudia Dukats and Danaye Mylonas – Residential Care Funding Reform Branch, Department of Health and Aged Care
• Angela Tulk – Services Australia

title: COVID-19 safe behaviours
description:
There are some easy but important steps we can all take to help protect ourselves and the health system. This includes wearing a mask and remembering physical distancing and good hygiene. Also testing if you have symptoms and staying home if you have COVID-19.  
Find out more at australia.gov.au

Transcript:
New variants are currently causing a surge in COVID-19 cases. 
There are some important ways you can protect yourself, others and our healthcare system.
When leaving home please wear a mask when indoors or in crowded places.
Cover your cough and wash your hands.
Remember physical distancing. 
Test if you have symptoms and stay home if you have COVID-19.
Together we can help slow the spread.

Visit Australia.gov.au.

Authorised by the Australian Government, Canberra.

title: Take on Winter
description:
Add your Flu shot and staying up to date with COVID-19 vaccinations to your winter to-do list. Visit australia.gov.au.

Transcript:
Beanies, scarves, fluffy socks, rummage through that winter box.
Warm soups, oversized knits, dig into those footy kits.
Add getting your Flu shot and staying up to date with your COVID-19 vaccinations to your winter to-do list.
It’s safe to get both vaccines at the same time.
And it’s never been more important with people being more vulnerable to illnesses this winter.
Book today at your GP or participating pharmacy.
Authorised by the Australian Government Canberra.

title: Medical Research Future Fund Webinar – 12 April 2022
description:
This video is a recording of a MRFF webinar on 12 April 2022. The webinar was hosted by Dr Masha Somi, Chief Executive Officer, Health and Medical Research Office. Our guest speaker was Ms Sue MacLeman, Chair of the MTPConnect Board.

Topics include:
• a Medical Research Future Fund (MRFF) update
• the 2nd 10-Year Investment Plan
• MTPConnect

title: Nurse Priscilla explains why you should get a COVID-19 vaccine booster dose
description:
In this video, nurse Priscilla explains why you should get a COVID-19 vaccine booster dose

Transcript:
I’m Nurse Priscilla, and I’m encouraging all our Mob to get out there and get a COVID-19 booster.  
With borders open and COVID now more common, I know a lot of you are wondering whether you even need a booster. 

Maybe you’re double vaxxed and you think that’s enough. Maybe you’ve already caught COVID so you think there’s no point.  Or maybe you’ve been double vaccinated AND caught COVID, so you’re thinking ‘why get another jab’. 

I’m here to tell you, boosters work. 

Yes, it is still possible to catch COVID if you’ve been vaccinated and boosted. And for some people sickness from COVID-19 can be mild. But that doesn’t mean it’s not dangerous. People still die from it and many end up in hospital.

But being vaccinated and boosted means there’s a much lower risk of becoming seriously ill or going to hospital if you catch COVID-19, as well as a lower risk of dying. I’ve seen it for myself. 

And remember, boosters don’t just build up your protection and reduce severe illness. They may also reduce the chances of COVID-19 spreading in your home and the community, so the more people that get them, the more protected we are. 

Have a yarn with your local community pharmacy, GP or healthcare worker about getting a booster, 
or visit health.gov.au.

title: Dr Aleeta explains why it’s important for kids to get vaccinated against COVID-19
description:
Dr Aleeta explains why it’s important for kids to get vaccinated against COVID-19

Transcript:
We know the best protection from COVID-19 is getting vaccinated.  But it’s natural for parents to have questions about giving their kids the jab. So I’m going to try and answer those questions for you. 

I’ve heard that COVID isn’t as bad in kids so why do they need the vaccine? 

COVID-19 is a serious illness that can affect everyone—including children. Vaccines can help stop your child becoming very sick, or even dying, if they catch the virus. Vaccines may also help protect against a serious inflammatory syndrome that can occur in a small number of children after they get COVID-19. Being vaccinated can also reduce the chances of passing the virus on to others.  Which helps protect the whole community. 

Are vaccines safe for kids?

Rest assured, all vaccines that have been approved for use in children have been 
rigorously tested before being given the seal of approval. So they’re fine for kids to get.

My grandchild's scared of needles. What advice can I give my daughter?

Healthcare workers are used to seeing kids who are scared of needles, and can help to make it less scary for them. Often, the calmer you are , the more calm they’ll be.  It could help to bring a toy or friend. Distracting them can go a long way! 

And how many vaccinations do kids have to get? 

Kids are smaller than adults, so they get a smaller dose of the vaccine. Like all of us, however, they need more than one vaccine dose to stay up to date and get the best immunity. 

Is there any side effects I have to worry about for my son?

Like adults, kids might experience some mild side effects after their vaccine. Side effects are perfectly normal and are actually a sign that the vaccine is teaching your child’s body 
how to fight the virus. 

The sorts of things you’d see after any vaccination can include, fever, chills, headache and soreness where they’ve been injected. They don’t happen to everyone, and don’t usually last too long. 

My son's had COVID, does he even need the vaccine? 

Catching COVID-19 will give your child some immunity, but we’re not sure how much or for how long, so it’s important they still get vaccinated after they’ve recovered. This helps to further protect them for longer. 

I’ve heard lots of scary stories about the vaccination and I'm worried about my grandchildren.

Fake stories and misinformation are unfortunately very common, especially on social media. But even if you know they’re not true, they can leave a scary picture in your mind! The safety of COVID-19 vaccinations continue to be monitored in Australia and around the world. 

If you’re worried in any way, have questions or just want to yarn about getting your kids vaccinated,  talk to your local healthcare worker.

You can also call the National Coronavirus Helpline on 1800 020 080.

So help protect your kids, your family and your Mob, and get your kids vaccinated.

title: Dr Mark Wenitong explains how to use a saliva rapid antigen test (RAT)
description:
In this video, Dr Mark Wenitong explains how to use a saliva rapid antigen test (RAT).

Transcript:
Hi, I’m Dr Mark Wenitong, 

and I want to show all you Mob the right way to use a Rapid Antigen Test  – or RAT Test – to check to see if you have COVID-19.

If you’ve been in contact with someone who has COVID-19 or you have symptoms like fever or cough, it’s good to test to see if you have COVID.

A RAT can be an easy way to see whether or not you have COVID and you can do the test yourself without a doctor, in the comfort of your own home, and get the results in just 10 to 20 minutes. 

You can buy RATs from your local pharmacy, supermarket and lots of other retail stores,
as well as online.

You can also check on your state or territory health department website.

If you have a valid Commonwealth concession card you may be eligible to receive up to 10 free RATs, 
over 3 months from a participating community pharmacy.

There are a few different types of RAT kits available – but the three most common are -

one that tests the spit from your mouth, one that you suck like a lollipop, and one that takes a sample from your nose. 

Remember, no matter what test you have, before you start, wash your hands....

… and make sure you have a watch or timer handy.

If you’re using a RAT that tests your spit you’ll find
A strip that will show you if you have COVID-19 or not 
A tube 
A mouth piece to spit in 
A lid 
A small pack with a liquid called the buffer 

First, attach the mouth piece and squeeze the tube in the middle. 

Spit into the mouth piece. 

Stop squeezing the tube. 

Then take the mouth piece off. 

Open the pack with the buffer and pour it into the tube, making sure not to get any of it on your skin or eyes. 

Put the lid on the tube and squeeze the bottom part 10 to 15 times.

Get the strip that will show you if you have COVID-19. 

It has a small round circle at the bottom.

Squeeze two drops from the tube onto the circle and set your timer for 15 minutes.

Then, you wait.

No matter what type of test you use, once your timer is up, check the strip to see what it says. 

Make sure you do it straight away, as it can be inaccurate if you leave it too long. 

One RAT even has a torch to help you read the strip.

If you see a line next to the C, you don’t have COVID-19.

If you see a line next to the C and the T, you are positive for COVID-19.

If you only see one line next to the letter T, or no lines at all, your test didn’t work and you’ll need to do another test.

If you do test positive remember to isolate tell everyone you’ve been in touch with in the past few days that you’ve tested positive, and let your state or territory know your results. 

If you’re worried about your symptoms, or if you have other health conditions call the National Coronavirus Helpline or speak to your healthcare worker. 

So remember, if you need to test yourself for COVID-19, get a RAT. 

It’s easy and will help keep all us Mob safe. 

If you need to know more, have a yarn with your local healthcare worker or visit health.gov.au.

title: Dr Mark Wenitong explains how to use a lollipop rapid antigen test (RAT)
description:
In this video, Dr Mark Wenitong explains how to use a lollipop rapid antigen test (RAT).

Transcript:
Hi, I’m Dr Mark Wenitong, and I want to show all you Mob the right way to use a Rapid Antigen Test – or RAT Test – to check to see if you have COVID-19.

If you’ve been in contact with someone who has COVID-19, or you have symptoms like fever or cough, it’s good to test to see if you have COVID.

A RAT can be an easy way to see whether or not you have COVID. 

And you can do the test yourself without a doctor, in the comfort of your own home,  and get the results in just 10 to 20 minutes.

You can buy RATs from your local pharmacy, supermarket and lots of other retail stores, as well as online. 

You can also check on your state or territory health department website.

If you have a valid Commonwealth concession card you may be eligible to receive up to 10 free RATs, 
over 3 months from a participating community pharmacy.

There are a few different types of RAT kits available – but the three most common are one that tests the spit from your mouth, one that you suck like a lollipop, and one that takes a sample from your nose. 

Remember, no matter what test you have, before you start, wash your hands and make sure you have a watch or timer handy.

If you’re using a RAT that you suck like a lollipop you’ll find

A strip that will show you if you have COVID-19 or not, a lollipop saliva swab, a bag to use to throw your used test away.

First, take the lollipop out of the packet. 

Place the sponge end in your mouth, but don’t bite it. Move the swab back and forth in the front and sides of your mouth for 90 seconds.

Take the lollipop swab out of your mouth after 90 seconds, once the sponge is soft and the circle on the back turns blue.

Get the strip that will show you if you have COVID-19. It has a spot in the bottom where you put your test.

Insert the swab at the end of the lollipop into the strip and push down until it clicks into place.

Set your timer for 10 minutes.

Then, you wait.

No matter what type of test you use, once your timer is up, check the strip to see what it says. 

Make sure you do it straight away, as it can be inaccurate if you leave it too long. One RAT even has a torch to help you read the strip.

If you see a line next to the C, you don’t have COVID-19.

If you see a line next to the C and the T, you are positive for COVID-19.

If you only see one line next to the letter T, or no lines at all, your test didn’t work and you’ll need to do another test.

If you do test positive remember to isolate, tell everyone you’ve been in touch with in the past few days that you’ve tested positive, and let your state or territory know your results.

If you’re worried about your symptoms, or if you have other health conditions call the National Coronavirus Helpline or speak to your healthcare worker.

So remember, if you need to test yourself for COVID-19, get a RAT. It’s easy and will help keep all us Mob safe.

If you need to know more, have a yarn with your local healthcare worker or visit health.gov.au.

title: Dr Mark Wenitong explains how to use rapid antigen tests (RATs)
description:
Transcript:
Hi, I’m Dr Mark Wenitong, and I want to show all you Mob the right way to use a Rapid Antigen Test – or RAT Test – to check to see if you have COVID-19. If you’ve been in contact with someone who has COVID-19, or you have symptoms like fever or cough, it’s good to test to see if you have COVID. A RAT can be an easy way to see whether or not you have COVID. And you can do the test yourself without a doctor, in the comfort of your own home,  and get the results in just 10 to 20 minutes. You can buy RATs from your local pharmacy, supermarket and lots of other retail stores, as well as online. You can also check on your state or territory health department website. If you have a valid Commonwealth concession card you may be eligible to receive up to 10 free RATs,  
over 3 months from a participating community pharmacy. There are a few different types of RAT kits available – but the three most common are one that tests the spit from your mouth, one that you suck like a lollipop, and one that takes a sample from your nose. Remember, no matter what test you have, before you start, wash your hands and make sure you have a watch or timer handy. If you’re using a RAT that tests your spit you’ll find 
A strip that will show you if you have COVID-19 or not, a tube, a mouth piece to spit in, a lid, a small pack with liquid called the buffer. First, attach the mouth piece and squeeze the tube in the middle. Spit into the mouth piece. Stop squeezing the tube. Do this until the spit gets to the first line at the bottom of the tube  Open the pack with the buffer and pour it into the tube, making sure not to get any of it on your skin or eyes.  Put the lid on the tube and squeeze the bottom part 10 to 15 times. Get the strip that will show you if you have COVID-19. It has a small round circle at the bottom. Squeeze two to three drops from the tube onto the circle and set your timer for 15 minutes. Then, you wait. If you’re using a RAT that you suck like a lollipop you’ll find a strip that will show you if you have COVID-19 or not, a lollipop saliva swab, a bag to use to throw your used test away. First, take the lollipop out of the packet. Place the sponge end in your mouth, but don’t bite it. Move the swab back and forth in the front and sides of your mouth for 90 seconds. Take the lollipop swab out of your mouth after 90 seconds, once the sponge is soft and the circle on the back turns blue. Get the strip that will show you if you have COVID-19. It has a spot in the bottom where you put your test. Insert the swab at the end of the lollipop into the strip and push down until it clicks into place. Set your timer for 10 minutes. Then, you wait. If you’re using a RAT that takes a sample from your nose, inside your kit you’ll find a strip that will show you if you have COVID-19 or not, a long stick with 1 soft end, a tube with lid and a small pack with liquid called the buffer. Some kits also have a stand and a torch. First, make sure you have the tube the right way up. Your test kit might come with a stand to help. Be careful not to let the tube fall over. Open a pack with a buffer and pour it into the tube, making sure to not get any on your skin or eyes. Take the stick out of the packet, making sure you don’t touch the soft part of the stick. Put the soft part up your nose, all the way up until it you feel it touch the back of your nose. Keep moving the stick around. Use the soft end of the same stick and do the other side of your nose. When you’re done put the stick into the tube and stir it 10 times. Then, gently squeeze the sides of the tube together 10 times before taking the stick out. Put the cap tightly on the tube. Put the cap tightly on the tube. Get the strip that will show you if you have COVID-19. Squeeze three or four drops from the tube onto the circle at the bottom and set your timer for 10, 15 or 20 minutes, depending on what your kit says And you wait. No matter what type of test you use, once your timer is up, check the strip to see what it says.  Make sure you do it straight away, as it can be inaccurate if you leave it too long. One RAT even has a torch to help you read the strip. If you see a line next to the C, you don’t have COVID-19. If you see a line next to the C and the T, you are positive for COVID-19. If you only see one line next to the letter T, or no lines at all, your test didn’t work and you’ll need to do another test. If you do test positive remember to isolate tell everyone you’ve been in touch with in the past few days that you’ve tested positive,  and let your state or territory know your results. If you’re worried about your symptoms, or if you have other health conditions call the National Coronavirus Helpline or speak to your healthcare worker. So remember, if you need to test yourself for COVID-19, get a RAT. It’s easy and will help keep all us Mob safe. If you need to know more, have a yarn with your local healthcare worker or visit health.gov.au.

title: Dr Mark Wenitong answers questions about COVID-19 vaccines for children aged 5-11 years
description:
In this video, Dr Mark Wenitong answers questions about COVID-19 vaccines for children aged 5 to 11 years.

Transcript:
Speaker 1
We know the best protection from COVID-19 is getting vaccinated.
But it’s natural for parents to have questions about giving their kids the jab. 
So I’m going to try and answer those questions for you.

Speaker 2
I’ve heard that COVID isn’t as bad in kids so why do they need the vaccine?

Speaker 1
COVID-19 is a serious illness that can affect everyone—including children. 
Vaccines can help stop your child becoming very sick, or even dying, if they catch the virus. 
Vaccines may also help protect against a serious inflammatory syndrome that can occur in a small number of children after they get COVID-19. 
Being vaccinated can also reduce the chances of passing the virus on to others. 
Which helps protect the whole community.

Speaker 3
Are vaccines safe for kids?

Speaker 1
Rest assured, all vaccines that have been approved for use in children have been rigorously tested before being given the seal of approval. So they’re fine for kids to get.

Speaker 4
My daughter's scared of getting needles, how can we help her? 

Speaker 1
Healthcare workers are used to seeing kids who are scared of needles, and can help to make it less scary for them.  Often, the calmer you are , the more calm they’ll be. It could help to bring a toy or friend.  Distracting them can go a long way!

Speaker 5
And how many vaccinations do kids have to get? 

Speaker 1
Kids are smaller than adults, so they get a smaller dose of the vaccine. 
Like all of us, however, they need more than one vaccine dose to stay up to date and get the best immunity. 

Speaker 6
Are there any side effects I need to worry about for my kids?

Speaker 1
Like adults, kids might experience some mild side effects after their vaccine. 
Side effects are perfectly normal and are actually a sign that the vaccine is teaching your child’s body how to fight the virus. 
The sorts of things you’d see after any vaccination can include fever, chills, headache and soreness where they’ve been injected. 
They don’t happen to everyone, and they don’t usually last too long. 

Speaker 7
My kids have actually had COVID, so do they even need the vaccine? 

Speaker 1
Catching COVID-19 will give your child some immunity, but we’re not sure how much or for how long, so it’s important they still get vaccinated after they’ve recovered. This helps to further protect them for longer.

Speaker 8
I’ve heard lots of scary stories of kids being harmed by vaccinations and I’m worried for my grand kids. 

Speaker 1
Fake stories and misinformation are unfortunately very common—especially on social media. 
But even if you know they’re not true, they can leave a scary picture in your mind. 
The safety of COVID-19 vaccines continue to be monitored in Australia and around the world.
If you’re worried in any way, have questions or just want to yarn about getting your kids vaccinated, 
talk to your local healthcare worker. You can also call the National Coronavirus Hotline on 1800 020 080.
So help protect your kids, your family and your Mob, and get your kids vaccinated.

title: Dr Mark Wenitong explains why you should get your COVID-19 vaccine booster dose
description:
In this video, Dr Mark Wenitong explains why you should get your COVID-19 vaccine booster dose.

Transcript:
I’m Dr Mark Wenitong, and I’m encouraging all our Mob to get out there and get a COVID-19 booster.

With borders open and COVID now more common, I know a lot of you are wondering whether you even need a booster. 

Maybe you’re double vaxxed and you think that’s enough. 

Maybe you’ve already caught COVID so you think there’s no point and maybe you’ve been double vaxxed and caught COVID, so you’re thinking ‘why get another jab’?

I’m here to tell you, boosters work.

Yes, it is still possible to catch COVID if you’ve been vaccinated and boosted. 

And for some people sickness from COVID-19 can be mild. 

But that doesn’t mean it’s not dangerous. People still die from it and many end up in hospital.

But being vaccinated and boosted means there’s a much lower risk of becoming seriously ill or going to hospital  if you catch COVID-19, as well as a lower risk of dying. 

I’ve seen it for myself.

 And remember, boosters don’t just build up your protection and reduce severe illness. 

They may also reduce the chances of COVID-19 spreading in your home and the community, 
so the more people that get them, the more protected we are.

Have a yarn with your local community pharmacy, GP or healthcare worker about getting a booster,  
or visit health.gov.au

title: Pacific Labour Scheme Webinar
description:
A webinar about the Pacific Labour Scheme and other aged care workforce initiatives to help rural and remote providers grow a skilled workforce. 

This webinar was held on 15 December 2021.

Timings

0.00 Emma Gleeson, Aged Care Workforce Branch, Department of Health
6.07 Michelle Tuchin, Skilled Visa Branch, Department of Home Affairs
12.48 Anna McNicol, Pacific Labour Policy & Programming, Department of Foreign Affairs
16.48 Alison Boundy, Pacific Labour Facility
38.41 Elizabeth Mandelkow, Bolton Clarke

The panel covered the following topics:

• Aged care workforce initiatives
• Overview of skilled migration visa requirements
• How rural and remote providers can use the Pacific Labour Scheme to access Pacific and Timorese aged care workers, and
• An employer’s perspective of the Pacific Labour Scheme.

Several questions were answered at the end of the webinar.

For more information on the Pacific Labour Scheme go to
https://www.dfat.gov.au/geo/pacific/engagement/pacific-labour-mobility

For more information on Aged Care Reforms
https://www.health.gov.au/aged-care-reforms

title: Release of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan
description:
The National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan 2021-2031 (Health Plan) is the new national policy to improve health and wellbeing outcomes for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people over the next 10 years.

The Health Plan has been released in partnership between the Australian Government, state and territory governments and Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health leaders. It demonstrates what can be achieved when co-design is based on empowerment, trust and mutual respect. 

This video includes messages about the release of the Health Plan from:
•The Hon Greg Hunt MP, Minister for Health and Aged Care
•Ms Donna Murray, CEO of Indigenous Allied Health Australia, Co-chair of the Health Plan Working Group
•Professor Tom Calma AO, National Co-ordinator, Tackling Indigenous Smoking, Deputy Chair of the Health Plan Working Group
•Ms Pat Turner, CEO of the National Aboriginal Community Controlled Organisation
•The Hon Key Wyatt AM MP, Minister for Indigenous Australians 
•Senator the Hon Richard Colbeck, Minister for Senior Australians and Aged Care Services, and Minister for Sport
•The Hon Dr David Gillespie, Minister for Regional Health
•The Hon David Coleman MP, Assistant Minister to the Prime Minister for Mental Health and Suicide Prevention

title: Release of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan – Minister Coleman
description:
**Please note captions will be provided soon for this video. 

Well I join Minister Hunt, Minister Wyatt and others in welcoming the release of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan 2021 to 31. As in too many other areas of health, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people disproportionately suffer mental ill-health and suicide. Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people are 2.4 times more likely to experience psychological distress than non-Indigenous adults. And tragically, the suicide rate is nearly twice the rate of non-Indigenous Australians. We all have a collective responsibility to change this, and it is something that the Australian Government is deeply committed to. The refreshed Health Plan has clear priorities for improving outcomes in mental health, suicide prevention, and social and emotional wellbeing. It includes a focus on the protective aspects of culture, spanning the relationships between individuals, families, kin and community, as well as connection to land, language, and culture. Importantly, the Health Plan ensures a wraparound approach to mental health and suicide prevention. It embeds collaboration across governments and portfolios at all levels, with mainstream health and mental health programs, private and non-profit sectors, and Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander services and organisations. The Health Plan’s approach aligns with key policies, including the National Agreement on Closing the Gap and the National Mental Health and Suicide Prevention Plan announced in May of this year. As well as our recent $79 million dollar budget package for Indigenous Australians, which includes the establishment of culturally sensitive, co-designed aftercare services for Indigenous Australians, and a 24/7 crisis line that will be governed and delivered by Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples in partnership with Lifeline and Gayaa Dhuwi. I applaud the Health Plan for its strong focus on suicide prevention and mental wellbeing. As with other health issues addressed in the plan, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander-led solutions, coupled with culturally safe and responsive support services, will be vital for progress.

title: Release of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan – Minister Gillespie
description:
**Please note captions will be provided soon for this video. 

Hi, almost two thirds of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Australians live in inner regional, outer regional, remote or very remote areas, and these populations already have poorer health outcomes than people living in metropolitan areas, just due to their location. The National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan for the decade recognises that care for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people needs to be place-based and centred on the person. Health services and organisations need to respond to the different experiences across urban, regional and remote locations. The Plan includes a focus on important environmental aspects such as housing, food and water security, and risk factors such as alcohol, tobacco and other drugs which can be heightened in rural and remote areas. Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people living in remote areas usually access primary health care from a GP who is part of an Aboriginal Medical Service or a community clinic. And that’s why the Health Plan has a focus on extending the reach of community controlled health services into areas of unmet need. This includes a focus on sustained capacity building to improve culturally safe service coverage and access to Care on Country. It also requires the continued expansion of point-of-care testing, telehealth and other digital technologies. The Plan recognises that a placed-based approach is also critical for culturally safe responses in times of challenge, such as what we’ve seen during the COVID-19 pandemic. Finally, the Plan seeks to grow the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander health workforce in rural, regional and remote areas. As the Minister for Regional Health, I welcome the Plan’s vision for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Australians living outside the cities.

title: Release of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan – Minister Wyatt
description:
**Please note captions will be provided soon for this video. 

Kaya Wanju - hello and welcome. Thank you for inviting me to address the launch of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan 2021 to 2031. I’m joining you from Ngunnawal country and my pay my respects to elders past, present and emerging. I’d also like to acknowledge the traditional owners of all the lands and waters across Australia. I’m pleased to join my ministerial colleagues, and Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander health leaders, in launching this landmark plan. The Health Plan is the culmination of strong partnerships with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people, and demonstrates what can be achieved when we all work together. In fact, the Health Plan has embedded all four Priority Reforms of the National Agreement on Closing the Gap and will drive progress against its health specific targets. The Health Plan will address the Priority Reforms by continuing to have a strong focus on shared decision making and partnerships during the implementation, operating across all levels of health planning and service delivery; building the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander community controlled health sector to deliver high-quality comprehensive primary health care services; growing and sustaining Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander representation and leadership across the health, disability and Aged Care workforces; improving collection, access management and use of data at the local level, giving communities ownership and control over their data. Ensuring that Indigenous Australians are leading the decisions that impact on their own health and wellbeing will accelerate progress to improvement. I am very pleased the Health Plan reflects the diversity of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people as well as the importance of the cultural and social determinants of health and wellbeing. It has been in partnership that we have developed the health plan ,and it’s with our continued collective efforts that we will ensure Indigenous Australians enjoy the same health outcomes as all other Australians. Thank you and thank you for your endeavours.

title: Release of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan – Pat Turner
description:
**Please note captions will be provided soon for this video. 

Hello, my name is Pat Turner and I’m the CEO of NACCHO and the Lead convenor of the Coalition of Peaks. I want to acknowledge the traditional custodians on the lands I am speaking from today, here on Ngunnawal country. I welcome the release of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan 2021 to 2031. This Health Plan has four key priorities, working in partnership to build the Aboriginal community controlled health sector and its workforce, a focus on preventive health care, improving the system as a whole and building the evidence base around the health of our people. The Plan embeds and integrated life-course approach to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander health care and prioritises our holistic model of care. Critically, the Plan recognises the significant role the Aboriginal community health sector plays within Australia’s health care architecture. Our ACCHO sector is leading the way in the delivery of comprehensive primary health care services for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander People. This plan will guide future health policies and programs for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people. Implementation will enable ACCHOs to strengthen and grow so that they can continue to deliver integrated care and primary health care services over the next 10 years. It’s been a pleasure to work in genuine partnership with the Department of Health and other members of the advisory committee to jointly develop this strategy. This approach ensured that Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander voices led the way and reflects the needs and aspirations of our people. I look forward to continuing to work in partnership with the Department of Health and mainstream health services to drive the change that is needed to improve the health and wellbeing outcomes for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people, in alignment with the National Agreement on Closing the Gap.
