title: Release of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan – Donna Murray & Tom Calma
description:
**Please note captions will be provided soon for this video

Hello. I’d like to acknowledge the traditional custodians across the lands on which we’re meeting on here today, the Ngunnawal peoples of the ACT and surrounding region. I’d also like to acknowledge the traditional custodians across all of our nation groups and lands in which we have lived and looked after our waters, lands and seas for over 60,000 years. And thank our ancestors for the knowledges, the leadership, the perspectives and the strength to move forward with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples. I’m Donna Murray, I’m the CEO Indigenous Allied Health Australia, and I’m here with Professor Tom Calma as the Chair and Deputy-chair of the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan Working Group. This Health Plan could not have been achieved without Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people voicing their needs, aspirations and goals as determined by your families and communities. As Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people we know what is best for our health and wellbeing. We are the holders of our own cultural knowledges, our languages and our practices. It has been an honour to work with the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander health experts of the Health Plan Working Group and Implementation Plan Advisory Group. We have worked in true partnership with government to develop this Health Plan, and we have ensured that it reinforces the importance of strengths-based and rights-based approaches that imbed the cultural determinants and the social determinants of health. These approaches reflect our holistic ways of knowing and being that have continued unbroken for over 60,000 years. And this includes the fundamental role that connection to country, family, kinship and community play in our health and wellbeing. For there to be real and sustained change, health and wellbeing must be self-determined and relative to place-based needs. This means aligning new and current investment with the Health Plan to ensure that it embeds our priorities. To enable real change, government policy-making and program implementation must include Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander self-determination, governance and leadership. We look forward to continuing to work on these partnerships with governments.
The Health Plan reflects the vision of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples. We want to enjoy long, healthy lives centred in culture with access to services that prevention-focused, culturally-safe and responsive, equitable and free from racism and discrimination. Our people and cultures are strong and resilient, and we have continued to see change and drive efforts for self-determination in health in all levels of our lives. But without a seat at the table, we will continue to see policies and practices implemented by governments that do not realise their full potential. For change to occur, our voices must be heard and departments and governments at every level must hear us. There must be shared commitments to truth telling and systemic change. Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people’s health is everybody’s business. All governments and sectors, including the mainstream, must work to ensure the whole health system is responsible to the needs of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health peoples, irrespective of where we live or who we are affiliated with. The Health Plan includes a long-term vision to eliminate racism with immediate action to address racism and discrimination across the health system. The Plan compliments the National Agreement including Priority Reform Three that aims to transform government organisations to work better for and with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health peoples. The development of this Health Plan demonstrates what can be achieved and when partnerships are based on empowerment, trust and mutual respect. It is this model of co-design practice that will set the standard for inspiring change across the whole health system and beyond. We hope that areas beyond the health sector can learn from the approach and work with us to close the gaps in health and life outcomes for our peoples.

title: Release of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan – Minister Hunt
description:
**Please note captions will be provided soon for this video. 

Well, welcome everybody to the launch of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan for 2021 to 2031 - a 10-year plan to help improve Indigenous health. And I just want to acknowledge Donna Murray, Tom Calma, Dawn Casey, Pat Turner and so many others who’ve assisted in the development of this plan. We know the challenge, Indigenous life-expectancy is still well below that of the Australian average. We know that the incidence of Health related issues is higher, but access to treatment is lower. That’s the central challenge. And the job will not be done, the gap will not be considered closed, until there’s no gap. There’s a no gap policy. That’s the only acceptable outcome - parity in health. So, the progress has been great. Whether it’s in terms of our children’s health, whether it’s reduction in smoking rates, whether it’s reduction in mortality, increase in life expectancy. But there is still a significant gap. And therefore, that’s why we need this 10-year plan, which is the result of a partnership. It has been developed by the Indigenous community for the Indigenous community, and it’s been our privilege and pleasure to assist in that process and our great responsibility to ensure that this is put into action. At the last budget, over $781 million dollars of additional funding for Indigenous health. But this plan sets out a pathway to making real differences. And it covers three broad areas, firstly, we need to recognise the social determinants of health, education, employment, housing, all of these have a profound impact on health. And health in turn, can have an impact on them. And so, it has to be a comprehensive solution for Indigenous Australians. The second thing is the health markers themselves. Of working to ensure that there is access and there are initiatives which we are taking in the coming mid-year economic forecasts, which build on the $781 million dollars that we put in place in the last budget and the work of previous years. And in particular, this is about focusing on access to doctors and the great revolution of telehealth, as well as incentives for medical professionals to operate in Indigenous Australia are so important. But the training of young Indigenous Australians as doctors, as nurses, allied health professionals, Indigenous health workers. That is indispensable, because if people come from community, they arere more likely to understand community and to come back to community. So, that workforce is such a critical and indispensable part of the task. And then lastly, there are specific initiatives. For me, working with Pat, and Dawn, and Donna, and Tom and so many others. The goals of ending avoidable Indigenous blindness by 2025, of ending avoidable Indigenous deafness by 2025, of ending rheumatic heart fever as a fatal condition by 2030. These are real, tangible, significant, not to be compromised upon. These are things for which to fight, and it’s my privilege to be able to join you in that battle around tangible specific goals, which will deliver better outcomes. There are so many things. I want to thank you and honour you for your work in developing this Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan for 2021 to 2031, and I am delighted to launch the Indigenous Health 10-year plan.

title: Release of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan – Senator Colbeck
description:
**Please note captions will be provided soon for this video. 

Elders have a special place for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people. They are the knowledge holders, caregivers, leaders and teachers. I welcome the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Plan for recognising the place of Elders, and the importance of living well into old age – a key focus of the Australian Government.
While Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people are living longer, so are all other Australians. That means the gap in life expectancy hasn’t narrowed. I am pleased to say that it is key focus of the new National Agreement, which seeks to Close the Gap in life expectancy within a generation, by 2031. The Health Plan recognises that different factors impact ageing well in different stages in life, and that we all need to work together in partnership with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders to bridge the gap in life expectancy. The Health Plan has a strong focus on culturally safe and responsive aged care that supports connection to culture, Country, family and community. As heard through the Aged Care Royal Commission, this includes the need for aged care services to be delivered by Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander providers. The Government’s aged care reform package, which responded to the Royal Commission, includes over $570 million dollars to improve the experience and care of older Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people. We are assisting the Aboriginal Community Controlled Health Services to expand into aged care and increasing Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander participation in the aged care workforce. As the Minister for Sport, I welcome the whole of life approach that the Health Plan takes to ensure Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people remain active as long as possible and make healthy lifestyle choices, including good nutrition. We want to see Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people enjoy long and healthy lives, from birth, right through to their place as Elders in the oldest living culture.

title: The South Hedland locals, come together at Wirraka Maya Health Service to protect the community
description:
The South Hedland locals, have come together at Wirraka Maya Health Service to protect the community by having the COVID-19 vaccine.

The locals from the remote WA town South Hedland, with a population of only about 9,500 people, have come together to protect the community by having the COVID-19 vaccine. ‘I think the people of Pilbara should get vaccinated, they’re protecting their family and this community’ Alfred Barker.

Transcript:
I'm pretty excited to be here today to get my first jab. 

I wanted to get vaccinated, to keep healthy and not get sick. 

I'm vaccinated because I think it's important to keep everybody in the community safe. 

I think the people of the Pilbara should get vaccinated, they're protecting their family and this community. 

This is really important because if you live in a remote area, we don't want us to be going to the hospital. 

We don't want us to be getting sick.

title: Dr Mark talks about the COVID-19 vaccine and side effects
description:
Dr Mark Wenitong, Aboriginal GP and Public Health MO talks about the COVID-19 vaccine and side effects. 

Transcript:
Hi, I’m Dr Mark Wenitong
Let’s talk about the COVID-19 vaccine and side effects.
Yes, some people get mild side effects from the jab, like headaches.
And there is a small risk of more serious side effects, like heart inflammation.
But it’s very, very rare.
Its way better, and safer to get the jab.
It helps stop you getting very sick or even dying.
And if you’re all vaccinated, the virus will have a harder time spreading in your community.
To find out more have a yarn with your local health care worker.

title: Spread Freedom – Thanks for getting vaccinated Australia (30 second TVC 1 )

title: Dr Mark addresses some of the stories around the COVID-19 virus
description:
Dr Mark Wenitong, Aboriginal GP and Public Health Medical Officer, addresses some of the stories around the COVID-19 virus.

Transcript:
G’day we need to yarn about all the crazy COVID-19 stories going around.
As a doctor working in Indigenous communities, I can tell you that COVID-19 is real, it is not a conspiracy and microchips are not being injected with the vaccine. Let’s listen to our scientists, not social media.
Vaccines can stop you getting very sick or dying from COVID-19. So get vaccinated!
If you want the facts, have a yarn with your local health care worker.

title: For all of us (15 second video featuring Indigenous musician, Baker Boy 4x5)
description:
COVID-19 has affected everyone in Australia. Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people from all over the country have come together for this campaign to encourage their family, friends, and community to protect themselves by getting the COVID-19 vaccine.
This video features music track Marryuna by Baker Boy. 
“I’m a proud Yolngu boy, and in Yolngu Matha, Marryuna means dancing. Dancing and music bring us all together and nothing makes me happier than performing and hitting the road to share my music with community.” Baker Boy
“I’m passionate about protecting my mobs’ culture, dance and music. But none of that matters unless we protect and safeguard our future and we can only do that by having a yarn to our health care workers about getting the COVID-19 jab.” Baker Boy

title: How My Aged Care can help you – Auslan captioned
description:
My Aged Care is the Australian Government's starting point on your aged care journey. This video gives a short overview of what My Aged Care is and how it supports you to find and access the government-funded services you need.

This video is live captioned using Auslan (Australian Sign Language). 

Transcript
My Aged Care is your starting point to access government funded aged care services.

Whatever your situation, specific needs, or background, we can help you understand what types of services are available. 

From services that help you live independently at home, to short term care that helps you get back on your feet, to moving into an aged care home when you can no longer live at home. 

Once you have the information you need, you can call us to discuss your needs and find out if you require an assessment. If you do, an assessor will come to your home for a face-to-face assessment to work out what services you are eligible for.

We can also help you estimate the fees you may have to pay and what service providers are available near you. 

Wherever you are on your aged care journey, My Aged Care can help you get started.

Find the help you need with My Aged Care. 

Go to myagedcare.gov.au, or call 1800 200 422.

title: Supporting in home and community aged care worker COVID-19 vaccination
description:
This short video provides information on why it is important for in home and community aged care workers to get vaccinated against COVID-19 to protect themselves and the people in their care. 

Transcript:
Aged care workers support senior Australians living at home and in the community to live their lives to the fullest.
Vaccination against COVID-19 is the best way to protect yourself and the people you care for. 
You can get vaccinated now with a choice of safe and effective vaccines.
Whether you’re a personal carer, a driver, a physiotherapist, a gardener or a volunteer, you need to be vaccinated.
Because when you protect yourself, you protect the people you care for. If you have concerns, talk to your GP.
I’m protected so you’re protected.
Book your vaccination today. Vaccine Clinic Finder at health.gov.au or call the dedicated COVID-19 helpline on 1800 020 080 (select option 4).

title: Catherine from Alice Springs says it’s your turn to do your part
description:
In this video, Eastern Arrernte woman Catherine reminds us that we all need two doses of the COVID-19 vaccine to be most protected.

Transcript:
I’m Catherine, I’m an Eastern Arrernte woman living in Mparntwe, Alice Springs.
As a Registered Nurse and a frontline worker, my colleagues and I have been working really hard to keep people safe. 
It’s really important that you’re fully vaccinated. To be fully vaccinated, you need two doses of your vaccination. That way you know that you are protected, and your community is protected as well. 
So you mob, now that we’ve got the vaccinations, it’s your turn to do your part.

Includes 30 minutes of Q&A with webinar participants.

title: COVID-19 aged care grief and trauma support services: support for grief, loss and bereavement
description:
Australian Centre for Grief and Bereavement
The Australian Centre for Grief and Bereavement (ACGB) provides tailored support, advice and specialised counselling with a bereavement practitioner in a one-to-one or group setting through:
• telehealth appointments
• video calls
• in-person appointments.
Online self-care resources are also available:
• webinars and fact sheets
• web chat
• SMS support
• MyGrief mobile app.
ACGB has bi-lingual staff who can work with clients in 12 languages: English, Arabic, Czech, Farsi, French, Italian, Japanese, Maltese, Sinhala, Tamil, Spanish, Yiddish.
To use Translating and Interpreting Support (TIS), call 131 450 first, nominate your language and ask to be connected to ACGB on 1800 22 2200.
For sign language interpreting services, contact Auslan Connections: http://www.auslanconnections.com.au/

title: Eddie from Alice Springs encourages everybody to get their COVID-19 vaccination
description:
Eddie, son of Eastern Arrernte woman Catherine, got his COVID-19 vaccine. He is encouraging everybody to get the COVID-19 vaccination, to help protect their families and communities.

Transcript:
G’day, my name is Eddie. I grew up in Alice Springs.

What’s important to me is freedom and at the moment this COVID-19 is really restricting our freedoms and it’s something that is quite foreign, you not being able to move about freely. 

So as soon as everybody is vaccinated, we’ll be able to move on with life. 

My advice to keep everybody safe, and your family and your community protected is to get the COVID-19 vaccination.

title: Getting your COVID-19 vaccine (Kimberley Kriol)
description:
This animation, translated into Kimberley Kriol, was produced for healthcare workers who work with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples. It can be used to support them explaining what the COVID-19 vaccination process will look like and what to expect during and after the vaccine.

Transcript:
We have heard about the COVID-19 sickness and how lots of people around the world, and in Australia, have gotten very sick and died from the disease.

We have been lucky in Australia, but as travel and tourism starts, we need to protect our elders and future generations.

There are new vaccines which will teach your body how to fight the COVID-19 sickness. The vaccines will protect you, your family and your community from getting really sick from COVID. 

You don’t have to have the vaccine, but it is strongly recommended. Make sure you get the vaccine when it is your turn. 

There are different types of the COVID-19 vaccine, and you will need to have two doses of the same. 

Before you get vaccinated, the clinic will ask you some health questions. First, they will ask if you have any allergies.

An allergy is when you come close to something and get sick very quickly.

You might get an itchy rash, your tongue might get big and you might breathe fast or cough lots.

Other questions you will get asked are about the medicines you take, if you have a weak immune system, if you are pregnant or breastfeeding, if you have a bleeding disorder or if you take medicine to thin your blood and if you have been sick recently.

The clinic will also ask your name and date of birth as well and who your closest family members are.

They will ask you if you understand all the information they have talked to you about, and if you agree to get the vaccine, you will have to sign a consent form to get the vaccine. 

To be vaccinated you will get a needle in your arm. You will need two needles on different days to be fully vaccinated against COVID-19.

Once you get the needle, the clinic nurse will get you to stay at the clinic for 15 minutes to make sure you are okay.

After you get the vaccine, you might get some mild side effects such as a sore arm, a headache, feeling tired or having a fever.

This should only last 1 to 2 days. It is normal and means the vaccine is working. 

If you have severe symptoms like a headache that won’t go away, are worried about how you are feeling or have any questions, make sure you talk to the health clinic.

title: Eastern Arrente family from Alice Springs tell us why they got vaccinated
description:
In this video, an Eastern Arrente family, Catherine, Lily, Eddie and Shanley, explain their reasons on why they chose to get vaccinated and encourage us all to do the same.

Transcript:
Catherine - The threat of Coronavirus is real. I chose to get fully vaccinated to protect my children, my grandchildren, the people of Alice Springs and our mob.
Catherine - Hello I'm Catherine.
Lily - Hi I'm Lily.
Eddie - Hi I'm Eddie.
Shanley - I'm Shanley.
Catherine - We're in Mparntwe country today and we're here to tell you our story about why we've chosen to get fully vaccinated.
Lily - I chose to get vaccinated, not only for my health but for my children and the Elders around me as well.
Eddie - Yeah look, for me its just about protecting the wider community, protecting myself and my family.
Shanley - I was definitely still nervous getting the vaccine but i feel like the clinic really educated me and answered all my questions around the vaccine. You can go ask those questions and even if they are silly, ask them and get educated on it and go get the vaccination.
Lily - Footy here in our community is a big part of our culture. If we can all get vaccinated we can all go to the footy again, be around our families, be around our friends and have the sense of community again. It'd be amazing.
Catherine - Its really important to get the two doses of the vaccines as well, to be fully vaccinated and protected.
Lily - We understand that our communities are quite far-out and sometimes it is hard to come into town and get your second dose, but there are vaccine staff that do go out to the communities and i urge our community mob to get vaccinated and get your second jab for everyone.
Shanley - Not only is it important to get vaccinated for our younger generation, buts its also really important to get vaccinated for our elders and our older generation. They hold so much cultural knowledge and sacred knowledge as it is and to keep them safe and to ensure that knowledge can be passed down to our younger generations is so important.
Catherine - I feel really safe and happy that I’m fully vaccinated and that my children are fully vaccinated and that we're contributing to the safety and the future of our community.
Eddie - Its not about ourselves, we've each got to do our bit for the wider community.

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak setting
description:
In this video, in English, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
Hi, I’m Dr Lucas de Toca and I lead the rollout of the vaccination program through GPs.

I wanted to update you on the use of the AstraZeneca vaccine given the increased risk of people becoming infected with the COVID-19 Delta strain at the moment. 

If you have had your first AstraZeneca dose at least four weeks ago, you should arrange your second dose as soon as possible. This advice has come from the Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation, or ATAGI.

Remember, for people aged 60 and over, the benefits of being vaccinated with the AstraZeneca vaccine strongly outweigh the risks. Vaccination is essential for this group in an outbreak.

Because supply of the Pfizer vaccine is limited right now, adults under the age of 60 should think about the benefits and risks of getting earlier protection through the AstraZeneca vaccine. You could talk to your doctor about it. Vaccination can provide increased benefits when there’s a higher risk of people getting COVID-19 in an outbreak.

Thank you. 

For more information, visit www.health.gov.au  

Call the disability gateway helpline on 1800 643 787, or visit the disability gateway website on www.disabilitygateway.gov.au 

If you are deaf, or have a hearing or speech impairment, you can call the National Relay Service on 133 677

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Swahili)
description:
In this video, with Swahili captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
Hi, mimi ni Daktari Lucas de Toca, na ninaongoza usambazaji wa mpango wa chanjo kupitia madkatari (GPs).
 
Nilitaka kukusasisha juu ya matumizi ya chanjo ya AstraZeneca, kutokana na ongezeko la hatari ya watu kuambukizwa ugonjwa wa virusi vya corona (COVID-19 Delta) kwa sasa.

Ikiwa umeshapata dozi yako ya kwanza ya AstraZeneca angalau wiki nne zilizopita, unapaswa kupanga dozi yako ya pili haraka iwezekanavyo.

Ushauri huu umetoka kwa Kikundi cha Ushauri wa Kiufundi cha Australia kuhusiana na Kinga au ATAGI.

Kumbuka, kwa watu wenye umri wa miaka 60 na zaidi, faida za kuchanjwa na chanjo ya AstraZeneca zinazidi sana kuliko hatari.

Chanjo ni muhimu kwa kikundi hiki katika wakati wa mlipuko.

Kwa sababu usambazaji wa chanjo ya Pfizer ni mdogo hivi sasa, watu wazima walio chini ya umri wa miaka 60 wanapaswa kufikiria juu ya faida na hatari ya kupata kinga ya mapema kupitia chanjo ya AstraZeneca.

Unaweza kuzungumza na daktari wako kuhusu hilo.

Chanjo inaweza kutoa faida zaidi wakati kuna hatari kubwa ya watu kupata ugonjwa wa virusi vya corona (COVID-19) katika mlipuko.

Asante.
 
Kwa maelezo zaidi, tembelea health.gov.au

Piga simu ya Msaada wa Walemavu kwenye 1800 643 787 au

tembelea tovuti ya disability Gateway kwenye  www.disabilitygateway.gov.au

Kama wewe ni kiziwi au una tatizo la kusikia au kusema, unaweza kupiga simu huduma ya kitaifa ya zamu ya ujumbe kwa 133 677

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Spanish)
description:
In this video, with Spanish captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
Hola, soy el Doctor Lucas de Toca y dirijo la implementación del programa de vacunación a través de médicos de cabecera.

Quería ponerlo al día sobre el uso de la vacuna AstraZeneca, dado el mayor riesgo de que las personas se infecten con la cepa Delta del COVID-19 en este momento.

Si recibió su primera dosis de AstraZeneca como mínimo cuatro semanas atrás, debería programar su segunda dosis lo antes posible.

Este consejo proviene del Grupo Asesor Técnico Australiano sobre Inmunización o ATAGI.
Recuerde, para las personas de 60 años en adelante, los beneficios de vacunarse con la vacuna AstraZeneca superan con creces los riesgos.

La vacunación es fundamental para este grupo en caso de un brote.

Debido a que el suministro de la vacuna Pfizer es limitado en este momento, los adultos menores de 60 años deberían considerar los beneficios y riesgos de obtener una protección más temprana a través de la vacuna AstraZeneca.

Podría hablar con su médico al respecto.

La vacunación puede proporcionar mayores beneficios cuando existe un alto riesgo de que las personas contraigan COVID-19 en un brote.

Gracias.

Para obtener más información, visite health.gov.au

Llame a la línea de ayuda de Disability Gateway, en el 1800 643 787 o
visite el sitio web de Disabled Gateway, en www.disabilitygateway.gov.au

Si es sordo o tiene una discapacidad auditiva o del habla, puede llamar al servicio de retransmisión nacional, en el 133 677

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Tongan)
description:
In this video, with Tongan captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
Mālō e lelei, ko au Toketā Lucas de Toca, pea ‘oku ou tataki ‘a hono kamata‘i ‘a e polokalama huhu malu‘í ‘o fakafou atu he kau toketā fakafāmili (GP’s).
 
‘Oku ou loto ke ‘oatu kiate koe ‘a e fakamatala fakamuimuitaha kau ki hono ngāue‘aki ‘o e faito‘o huhu malu‘i AstraZeneca, koe‘uhí ko e toe tu‘u laveangofua ange ‘a e tokolahi ke nau ma‘u ‘a e COVID-19 kalasi Delta ‘i he lolotonga ni.

Kapau kuo ‘osi ho ‘uluaki huhu AstraZeneca ‘i he uike ‘e fā kuo hilí ‘o ‘ikai toe nounou ange ai, ‘oku totonu leva ke ke alea‘i ke fai ho huhu hono uá he vave tahá.

Ko e fale‘i eni mei he Kulupu Fale‘i Fakatekinikale ‘a ‘Aositelelia ki he Huhu Malu‘i (Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation) pē ko e ATAGI.

Manatu‘i, ko e kakai ‘oku ta‘u 60 mo motu‘a angé, ko e ngaahi lelei ko ia hono huhu ‘aki ‘a e AstraZeneca ‘oku mahulu atu ia ‘i ha fakatu‘utāmaki ‘e ala hoko.

‘Oku mahu‘inga ‘aupito ‘a e huhu malu‘í ki he kulupu ko ení ‘i ha taimi ‘oku lahi ai e mafola ‘a e mahakí.

Koe‘uhí ‘oku lolotonga fakangatangata hono ma‘u mai e faito‘o huhu malu‘i ko ia ko e Pfizer, ‘oku totonu leva ki he kakai ‘oku nau si‘i hifo he ta‘u 60 ke nau fakakaukau felāve‘i mo hono lelei mo e uesia ‘e ala hoko ‘i hono ma‘u vave ko ia ha malu‘i ‘aki e huhu AstraZeneca.

Te ke lava ‘o fakatalanoa ki ho‘o toketā ‘o kau ki ai.

Ko e huhu malu‘í ‘oku ‘aonga lahi ia ‘i he taimi ‘oku ‘alu ke toe fakautuutu ange ai e tokolahi ‘o e kakai ‘oku nau puke ‘i he COVID-19 pea mo e mafola lahi ange ‘a e mahakí.

Mālō ‘aupito.
 
Ke ma‘u ha toe fakaikiiki ange, vakai ki he health.gov.au

Telefoni kihe Laine Tokoni ki he Kakai Faingata‘a‘ia (Disability Gateway Helpline) ‘i he fika 1800 643 787 pē

Vakai ki he ‘enau uepisaiti ‘a e Gateway ‘i he www.disabilitygateway.gov.au

Kapau ‘oku malu ho telinga (tuli) pe ‘i ai ha‘o palopalema ‘i ho‘o fanongó pē palopalema ‘i ho‘o leá, te ke lava ‘o tā ki he sēvesi fakafonua fakakahoko atú (the national relay service) ‘i he fika 133 677

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Vietnamese)
description:
In this video, with Vietnamese captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
Xin chào quý vị, tôi là Bác sĩ Lucas de Toca và tôi chỉ đạo việc triển khai chương trình tiêm chủng thông qua bác sĩ gia đình.
 
Tôi muốn báo cho quý vị thông tin cập nhật về việc sử dụng vắc-xin AstraZeneca, vì nguy cơ người dân bị nhiễm COVID-19 biến thể Delta đã gia tăng vào lúc này.

Nếu đã được tiêm liều AstraZeneca đầu tiên cách đây ít nhất bốn tuần, quý vị nên đặt hẹn để được tiêm liều thứ hai càng sớm càng tốt.

Nhóm Cố vấn Kỹ thuật Úc về Chủng ngừa hoặc ATAGI đã khuyên như vậy.

Xin nhớ rằng, đối với những người từ 60 tuổi trở lên, lợi ích của việc chủng ngừa với vắc-xin AstraZeneca vượt trội hơn so với các rủi ro.

Chủng ngừa là điều thiết yếu đối với nhóm người trên 60 tuổi này trong đợt bùng phát dịch bệnh.

Vì nguồn cung cấp vắc-xin Pfizer hiện giờ có hạn, người trưởng thành dưới 60 tuổi nên suy nghĩ về lợi ích và rủi ro của việc nhận được sự bảo vệ sớm hơn qua vắc-xin AstraZeneca.

Quý vị có thể nói chuyện với bác sĩ của mình về việc này.

Tiêm phòng có thể mang lại nhiều lợi ích hơn khi có nguy cơ cao người bị nhiễm COVID-19 trong đợt bùng phát dịch bệnh.

Cảm ơn quý vị đã đọc thông tin.
 
Để biết thêm thông tin, hãy truy cập health.gov.au

Hãy gọi cho Đường dây Cổng Thông tin dành cho Người Khuyết tật (Disability Gateway Helpline) qua số 1800 643 787 hoặc

truy cập trang mạng Cổng Thông tin cho Người Khuyết Tật (Disability Gateway) tại  www.disabilitygateway.gov.au

Nếu bị điếc, suy giảm thính lực hay nói khó khăn, quý vị có thể gọi cho dịch vụ tiếp âm toàn quốc qua số 133 677

In this video, with Sinhala captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.'

Transcript:
ආයුබෝවන්, මම වෛද්‍ය ලූකස් ඩි ටෝකා, වෛද්‍යවරු හරහා සිදු කරන එන්නත්කරණ වැඩසටහනේ ප්‍රධානත්වය දරන්නේ මමයි.
 
මට ඇස්ට්‍රාසෙනෙකා එන්නත භාවිතා කිරීම ගැන ඔබව යාවත්කාලීන කිරීමට අවශ්‍ය වුණා, ඊට හේතුව වන්නේ මෙම අවස්ථාවේ COVID-19 ඩෙල්ටා ප්‍රභේදයෙන් පුද්ගලයින් ආසාදනයට ලක්වීම සඳහා ඉහළ අවදානමක් ඇතිව තිබීමයි.

ඔබ විසින් ඔබේ ඇස්ට්‍රාසෙනෙකා එන්නතේ මාත්‍රාව එන්නත අවම වශයෙන් සති හතරකට, පෙර ලබා ගෙන ඇත්නම්, දෙවන මාත්‍රාව ලබා ගැනීම සඳහා ඉක්මණින්ම දිනයක් වෙන් කරවා ගන්න.

මෙම උපදේශය ලබා දී ඇත්තේ ඕස්ට්‍රේලියානු ප්‍රතිශක්තීකරණය පිළිබඳ තාක්ෂණික උපදේශන කණ්ඩායම හෙවත් ATAGI වෙතින්. 

මතක තබාගන්න, වයස අවුරුදු 60ට වැඩි පුද්ගලයින් සඳහා, එන්නත ලබා ගැනීමෙන් ලැබෙන ප්‍රතිලාභ ඉන් ඇති විය හැකි අවදානම්වලට වඩා බෙහෙවින් වැඩියි.

ශීග්‍රයෙන් රෝගය පැතිරෙන අවස්ථාවකදී එන්නත ලබා ගැනීම අත්‍යවශ්‍යයි.

මේ අවස්ථාවේදී ෆයිසර් එන්නතේ සැපයුම සීමාසහිත බැවින්, වයස අවුරුදු 60ට අඩු වැඩිහිටියන් ඇස්ට්‍රාසෙනෙකා එන්නත තුළින් ලැබෙන ප්‍රතිලාභ සහ ඉක්මන් ආරක්ෂාව ලබා ගැනීමේ ඇති අවදානම් ගැන කල්පනා කළ යුතුයි.

ඔබට ඒ ගැන ඔබේ වෛද්‍යවරයා සමඟ කතා කළ හැකිය. 

COVID-19 ශීග්‍රයෙන් රෝගය පැතිර යන අවස්ථාවකදී බොහෝ පුද්ගලයින්ට එය වැළඳීමේ ඉහළ අවදානමක් ඇති බැවින් එන්නත මගින් ඉහළ ප්‍රතිලාභ ලබා ගත හැකියි.

ස්තූතියි.
 
වැඩි විස්තර සඳහා health.gov.au වෙත යන්න 

1800 643 787 ඔස්සේ ආබාධිතතා ද්වාරමාර්ග උපකාරක දුරකථන සේවාව අමතන්න එසේ නැතහොත් 

 www.disabilitygateway.gov.au ඔස්සේ ආබාධිතතා ද්වාරමාර්ග වෙබ් අඩවිය වෙත පිවිසෙන්න 

ඔබ බිහිරි අයෙකු නම් හෝ ඔබට ශ්‍රවණ හෝ කථන ආබාධයක් ඇත්නම්, ඔබට 133 677 ඔස්සේ ජාතික සහායක සේවාව ඇමතිය හැකියි

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Samoan)
description:
In this video, with Samoan captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
Talofa, o a’u o Doctor Lucas de Toca, ma o a’u o lo’o  ta’ita’ia le polokalama o tui e ala atu i foma’i uma.
 
Ou te mana’o e fa’ailoa atu le fa’aaogāina o le tui o le AstraZeneca, talu ai le fa’ateleina o le ono a’afia o tagata i lenei fa’ama’i o le COVID-19 Delta strain i le taimi nei.

Pe afai ua uma lou tui muamua o le AstraZeneca i le fa vaiaso ua tuana’i atu, ua tatau nei loa ona fa’atulaga lou tui lona lua i le vave e mafai ai.

O lenei fautuaga ua tu’uina mai e le Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation (ATAGI).

Manatua, mo tagata matutua e 60 tausaga ma luga atu, o le aogā o le tuiina i le vaila’au o le AstraZeneca, e sili atu lona tāua nai lō le a’afiaga.

E tāua tele nei tui puipuia mo lenei vaega pe a afāina.

Talu ai ua fa’atapula’aina le aofa’iga o tui puipuia o le Pfizer mo le taimi nei, ua tatau i tagata matutua e 60 tausaga ma luga atu ona mafaufau i le aogä ma le lamatiaga o le vave maua o puipuiga e ala i le tui o le AstraZeneca.

E mafai ona e talanoa i lau foma’i e uiga i ia vaega.

O tui e mafai ona maua ma fa’ateleina le aogā pe a maualuga le lamatiaga o tagata e maua i le COVID-19 po’o se fa’ama’i.

Fa'afetai.
 
Mo nisi fa’amatalaga, asiasi i le health.gov.au

Vala’au le Disability Gateway Helpline i le 1800 643 787 po’o

asiasi i le upega tafa’ilagi a le Disability Gateway www.disabilitygateway.gov.au

A e tutuli pe leaga le faalogo ma lē malamalama le tautala, e mafai fo’i ona e faafesootaʻi mai matou i le National Relay Service (NRS) i le 133 677

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Punjabi)
description:
In this video, with Punjabi captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
ਸਤਿ ਸ਼੍ਰੀ ਅਕਾਲ ਜੀ, ਮੈਂ ਡਾਕਟਰ ਲੂਕਸ ਡੀ ਟੋਕਾ ਹਾਂ, ਅਤੇ ਮੈਂ GP's ਦੁਆਰਾ ਟੀਕਾਕਰਣ ਪ੍ਰੋਗ੍ਰਾਮ ਦੀ ਅਗਵਾਈ ਕਰ ਰਿਹਾ ਹਾਂ।
 
ਇਸ ਸਮੇਂ COVID-19 ਡੈਲਟਾ ਸਟਰੇਨ ਦੇ ਨਾਲ ਲੋਕਾਂ ਨੂੰ ਲਾਗ ਲੱਗਣ ਦੇ ਵੱਧ ਰਹੇ ਖਤਰੇ ਨੂੰ ਦੇਖਦੇ ਹੋਏ, ਮੈਂ ਤੁਹਾਨੂੰ ਐਸਟ੍ਰਾਜ਼ੈਨੇਕਾ ਟੀਕੇ ਦੀ ਵਰਤੋਂ ਬਾਰੇ ਅੱਪਡੇਟ ਕਰਨਾ (ਤਾਜ਼ਾ ਜਾਣਕਾਰੀ ਦੇਣਾ) ਚਾਹੁੰਦਾ ਸੀ।

ਜੇ ਤੁਹਾਨੂੰ ਘੱਟੋ-ਘੱਟ ਚਾਰ ਹਫ਼ਤੇ ਪਹਿਲਾਂ ਐਸਟ੍ਰਾਜ਼ੈਨੇਕਾ ਦੀ ਪਹਿਲੀ ਖੁਰਾਕ ਮਿਲੀ ਹੈ, ਤਾਂ ਤੁਹਾਨੂੰ ਜਲਦੀ ਤੋਂ ਜਲਦੀ ਆਪਣੀ ਦੂਜੀ ਖੁਰਾਕ ਦਾ ਪ੍ਰਬੰਧ ਕਰਨਾ ਚਾਹੀਦਾ ਹੈ।

ਇਹ ਸਲਾਹ ਟੀਕਾਕਰਨ ਬਾਰੇ ਆਸਟਰੇਲੀਆ ਦੇ ਤਕਨੀਕੀ ਸਲਾਹਕਾਰ ਸਮੂਹ ਜਾਂ ਏ.ਟੀ.ਏ.ਜੀ.ਆਈ.(ATAGI) ਵੱਲੋਂ ਦਿੱਤੀ ਗਈ ਹੈ।

ਯਾਦ ਰੱਖੋ ਕਿ, 60 ਸਾਲ ਜਾਂ ਇਸ ਤੋਂ ਵੱਧ ਉਮਰ ਦੇ ਲੋਕਾਂ ਲਈ, ਐਸਟ੍ਰਾਜ਼ੈਨੇਕਾ ਟੀਕਾ ਲਗਵਾਉਣ ਦੇ ਲਾਭ ਇਸ ਤੋਂ ਹੋਣ ਵਾਲੇ ਖਤਰਿਆਂ ਤੋਂ ਕਿਤੇ ਜ਼ਿਆਦਾ ਵੱਧ ਹਨ।

ਇਸ ਸਮੂਹ ਲਈ COVID-19 ਦੇ ਪ੍ਰਕੋਪ ਸਮੇਂ ਟੀਕਾਕਰਣ ਹੋਇਆ ਹੋਣਾ ਜ਼ਰੂਰੀ ਹੁੰਦਾ ਹੈ।

ਕਿਉਂਕਿ ਫਾਈਜ਼ਰ ਟੀਕੇ ਦੀ ਸਪਲਾਈ ਇਸ ਸਮੇਂ ਸੀਮਤ ਹੈ, ਇਸ ਲਈ 60 ਸਾਲ ਤੋਂ ਘੱਟ ਉਮਰ ਦੇ ਬਾਲਗਾਂ ਨੂੰ ਐਸਟ੍ਰਾਜ਼ੈਨੇਕਾ ਟੀਕੇ ਦੁਆਰਾ ਪਹਿਲਾਂ ਸੁਰੱਖਿਆ ਪ੍ਰਾਪਤ ਕਰਨ ਦੇ ਫਾਇਦਿਆਂ ਅਤੇ ਖਤਰਿਆਂ ਬਾਰੇ ਸੋਚਣਾ ਚਾਹੀਦਾ ਹੈ।

ਤੁਸੀਂ ਇਸ ਬਾਰੇ ਆਪਣੇ ਡਾਕਟਰ ਨਾਲ ਗੱਲ ਕਰ ਸਕਦੇ ਹੋ।

ਟੀਕਾਕਰਣ ਵਧੇਰੇ ਲਾਭ ਪ੍ਰਦਾਨ ਕਰ ਸਕਦਾ ਹੈ ਜਦੋਂ ਲੋਕਾਂ ਵਿੱਚ ਲਾਗ ਫ਼ੈਲੇ ਹੋਣ ਕਾਰਨ COVID-19 ਹੋਣ ਦੇ ਬਹੁਤ ਜ਼ਿਆਦਾ ਖਤਰੇ ਹੁੰਦੇ ਹਨ।

ਤੁਹਾਡਾ ਧੰਨਵਾਦ।
 
ਵਧੇਰੇ ਜਾਣਕਾਰੀ ਲਈ, health.gov.au 'ਤੇ ਜਾਓ

ਡਿਸਬਿਲਟੀ (ਅਪਾਹਜਤਾ) ਗੇਟਵੇਅ ਹੈਲਪਲਾਈਨ ਨੂੰ 1800 643 787 'ਤੇ ਫੋਨ ਕਰੋ  ਜਾਂ 

www.disabilitygateway.gov.au 'ਤੇ ਡਿਸਬਿਲਟੀ ਗੇਟਵੇਅ ਵੈਬਸਾਈਟ ਉੱਪਰ ਜਾਓ

ਜੇ ਤੁਸੀਂ ਬੋਲ਼ੇ ਹੋ ਜਾਂ ਤੁਹਾਡੀ ਸੁਣਨ ਜਾਂ ਬੋਲਣ ਸੰਬੰਧੀ ਕਮਜ਼ੋਰੀ ਹੈ, ਤਾਂ ਤੁਸੀਂ ਰਾਸ਼ਟਰੀ ਰਿਲੇਅ ਸੇਵਾ ਨੂੰ 133 677 'ਤੇ ਫੋਨ ਕਰ ਸਕਦੇ ਹੋ

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Korean)
description:
In this video, with Korean captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
안녕하세요, 저는 닥터 루카스 데 토카이며, GP를 통한 백신접종 실시를 이끌고 있습니다. 

현재 COVID-19 델타 변이 감염의 위험이 증가함에 따라, 아스트라제네카 백신 사용에 대한 정보 업데이트를 제공하고자 합니다. 

적어도 4주 전에 첫번째 아스트라제네카 백신을 맞았다면 최대한 빨리 두번째 접종을 준비하십시오. 

이는 호주예방접종기술자문그룹 즉, ATAGI의 권고사항입니다. 

기억하실 것은 60세 이상의 사람들에게 아스트라제네카 백신의 혜택이 위험보다 훨씬 더 크다는 사실입니다.  

이 발발상황에서 백신접종은 이 그룹에게 필수적입니다.  

지금 화이자 백신의 물량이 한정되어 있기 때문에, 60세 미만의 성인은 아스트라제네카 백신을 통한 좀더 이른 보호의 혜택 및 위험을 생각해봐야 할 것입니다. 

의사와 상의하십시오. 

백신접종은 이 발발 상황에서 사람들이 COVID-19에 걸릴 위험이 높을 때 혜택이 증가합니다. 

감사합니다. 
더 자세한 정보를 원하시면 health.gov.au를 방문하십시오. 
장애자 게이트웨이 전화 상담 서비스 1800 643 787번에 전화하거나, 장애자 게이트웨이
 웹사이트  www.disabilitygateway.gov.au를 방문하십시오. 

청각 혹은 언어 장애가 있다면, 전국 릴레이 서비스 133 677번으로 전화하십시오.

title: Dr Lucas de Toca talks about why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Italian)
description:
In this video, with Italian captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
Buongiorno, sono il dott. Lucas de Toca e dirigo l'implementazione del programma di vaccinazione tramite i medici di base.
 
Vorrei fornirvi un aggiornamento sull'utilizzo del vaccino di AstraZeneca, dato il maggior rischio di infezione delle persone con la variante Delta del COVID-19 al momento.

Se avete ricevuto la vostra prima dose di AstraZeneca almeno quattro settimane fa, dovreste organizzarvi per ricevere la seconda dose il prima possibile.

Questa raccomandazione proviene dall'Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation (ATAGI).

Ricordate che per le persone di età pari o superiore ai 60 anni i vantaggi della vaccinazione con AstraZeneca superano di gran lunga i rischi.

In un focolaio, la vaccinazione è essenziale per questo gruppo.

Poiché al momento la fornitura del vaccino di Pfizer è limitata, gli adulti che hanno meno di 60 anni dovrebbero riflettere sui rischi e benefici associati a una protezione precoce tramite il vaccino di AstraZeneca.

Potreste discuterne con il vostro medico.

La vaccinazione può fornire maggiori benefici quando vi è un rischio più elevato che le persone si ammalino di COVID-19 durante un focolaio.

Grazie.
 
Per maggiori informazioni visitate health.gov.au

Chiamate la Disability Gateway Helpline al 1800 643 787 o

visitate il sito web di Disability Gateway a  www.disabilitygateway.gov.au

Se siete non udenti o affetti da disturbi dell’udito o del linguaggio, potete chiamare il National Relay Service al 133 677

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Hindi)
description:
In this video, with Hindi captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
नमस्ते, मैं डॉक्टर ल्युकास डी टोका हूँ, और मैं जीपी (सामान्य डॉक्टरों) के माध्यम से टीकाकरण कार्यक्रम के रोलआउट का नेतृत्व करता हूँ।
 
मैं इस समय लोगों के लिए COVID-19 के डेल्टा प्रारूप से संक्रमित होने के बढ़ते खतरे को देखते हुए एस्ट्राज़ेनेका टीके के उपयोग पर आपको अपडेट करना चाहता था।

यदि आपने कम से कम चार सप्ताह पहले एस्ट्राज़ेनेका की अपनी पहली खुराक ली है, तो आपको जितनी जल्दी हो सके अपनी दूसरी खुराक की व्यवस्था करनी चाहिए।

यह सलाह ऑस्ट्रेलियाई टीकाकरण तकनीकी सलाहकार समूह या एटीएजीआई (Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation या ATAGI) की ओर से है।

याद रखें, 60 वर्ष और इससे अधिक आयु के लोगों के लिए एस्ट्राज़ेनेका का टीकाकरण कराने से खतरों की तुलना में लाभ कहीं अधिक हैं।

प्रकोप होने पर इस समूह के लिए टीकाकरण कराना आवश्यक है।

इस समय फाइज़र टीके की आपूर्ति सीमित है, इसलिए 60 वर्ष से कम आयु के वयस्कों को एस्ट्राज़ेनेका टीके से जल्दी संरक्षण कराने के लाभों और खतरों के बारे में सोचना चाहिए।

आप इसके बारे में अपने डॉक्टर से बात कर सकते/सकती हैं।

जब प्रकोप में लोगों के लिए COVID-19 से संक्रमित होने का ऊँचा खतरा होता है, तो टीकाकरण कराने से और अधिक लाभ मिल सकते हैं।

धन्यवाद।
 
और अधिक जानकारी के लिए वेबसाइट health.gov.au पर जाएँ

विकलांगता गेटवे हेल्पलाइन (Disability Gateway Helpline) को 1800 643 787 पर पर कॉल करें या

विकलांगता गेटवे (Disability Gateway) की वेबसाइट www.disabilitygateway.gov.au पर जाएँ

यदि आप बहरे/बहरी हैं या आपके सुनने या बोलने की क्षमता बाधित है, तो आप राष्ट्रीय रिले सेवा को 133 677 पर कॉल कर सकते/सकती हैं

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Greek)
description:
In this video, with Greek captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
Γεια σας, είμαι ο γιατρός Λούκας Ντε Τόκα (Lucas de Toca) και ηγούμαι της διαθεσιμότητάς του προγράμματος εμβολιασμού μέσω των παθολόγων γιατρών (GPs).

Ήθελα να σας ενημερώσω σχετικά με τη χρήση του εμβολίου AstraZeneca, δεδομένου του αυξημένου κινδύνου ατόμων που μολύνονται από το στέλεχος Δέλτα της COVID-19 αυτή την περίοδο.

Εάν λάβατε την πρώτη δόση σας με το εμβόλιο AstraZeneca πριν από τουλάχιστον τέσσερις εβδομάδες, θα πρέπει να κανονίσετε τη δεύτερη δόση σας το συντομότερο δυνατό.

Αυτή η σύσταση προέρχεται από την Αυστραλιανή Τεχνική Συμβουλευτική Ομάδα για Εμβολιασμούς ή ATAGI.

Να θυμάστε ότι για άτομα 60 ετών και άνω, τα οφέλη του εμβολιασμού με το εμβόλιο AstraZeneca αντισταθμίζουν σημαντικά τους κινδύνους.

Ο εμβολιασμός είναι απαραίτητος για αυτή την ομάδα σε περίοδο έξαρσης κρουσμάτων.

Επειδή η προμήθεια του εμβολίου Pfizer είναι περιορισμένη αυτή τη στιγμή, οι ενήλικες κάτω  των 60 ετών θα πρέπει να σκεφτούν τα οφέλη και τους κινδύνους για να προστατευτούν  γρηγορότερα μέσω του εμβολίου AstraZeneca.

Θα μπορούσατε να μιλήσετε με το γιατρό σας γι’ αυτό το ζήτημα.

Ο εμβολιασμός μπορεί να προσφέρει αυξημένα οφέλη όταν υπάρχει υψηλός κίνδυνος ατόμων  που μολύνονται από την COVID-19 σε περίοδο έξαρσης κρουσμάτων.

Ευχαριστώ.
 
Για περισσότερες πληροφορίες, επισκεφθείτε την health.gov.au

Καλέστε την Τηλεφωνική Γραμμή Βοήθειας Disability Gateway στο 1800 643 787 ή

Επισκεφθείτε τον ιστότοπο της Disability Gateway στο  www.disabilitygateway.gov.au
Εάν είστε κωφοί ή έχετε μια δυσκολία με την ακρόαση ή την ομιλία, μπορείτε να καλέσετε την Εθνική Υπηρεσία Αναμετάδοσης στο 133 677

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Tagalog)
description:
In this video, with Tagalog captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
Kumusta, ako si Doktor Lucas de Toca, at pinangungunahan ko ang pagpapalabas ng programa sa pagbabakuna sa pamamagitan ng mga GP.
 
Gusto kung isapanahon kayo tungkol sa paggamit ng bakunang AstraZeneca, dahil sa lumaking peligro ng mga tao na mahahawahan ng Delta strain ng COVID-19 ngayon.

Kung nabakunahan ka na ng una mong dosis ng AstraZeneca nang mga apat na linggo na ang nakaraan, dapat kang makipag-ayos para sa iyong ikalawang dosis sa pinakamadaling panahon.

Ito ang payo na galing sa Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation o ATAGI.

Tandaan, para sa mga taong may edad na 60 pataas, ang mga benepisyo sa pagbabakuna ng AstraZeneca ay mas nakalalamang kaysa mga peligro.

Ang pagbabakuna ay kinakailangan sa pangkat na ito kapag may pagsiklab.

Dahil ang panustos ng bakunang Pfizer ay limitado sa ngayon, ang mga may-edad na wala pang 60 na taong gulang ay dapat pag-isipan ang tungkol sa mga benepisyo at peligro sa pagkakaroon ng mas maagang proteksyon sa pamamagitan ng bakunang AstraZeneca.

Maaaring pag-usapan mo at ng iyong doktor ang tungkol dito.

Ang pagbabakuna ay maaaring makapagbigay ng karagdagang mga benepisyo kapag may mataas na peligro ng pagkakahawahan sa pagsiklab ng COVID-19.

Salamat po.
 
Para sa dagdag na impormasyon, bumisita sa health.gov.au

Tawagan ang Disability Gateway Helpline sa 1800 643 787 o bumisita sa website ng Disability Gateway sa www.disabilitygateway.gov.au

Kung ikaw ay may kapansanan sa pandinig o pananalita,  maaari mong tawagan ang national relay service sa 133 677

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Traditional Chinese)
description:
In this video, with Traditional Chinese captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
各位好，我是陸啟思 (Lucas de Toca) 醫生，全科醫生疫苗接種計劃是由我率領。

有見目前感染 COVID-19 Delta 病毒株的風險增加，我想向您講一講接種阿斯利康(AstraZeneca)疫苗的新資料。

若您已接種了第一劑阿斯利康疫苗4星期或以上，您應盡快接種第二劑。

此忠告來自澳洲免疫技術諮詢小組(ATAGI)。

請謹記，對於 60 歲及以上人士來說，接種阿斯利康疫苗的好處遠遠大於風險。

在疫症爆發時，接種疫苗對這一群組至關重要。

由於輝瑞 (Pfizer) 疫苗目前供應有限，60 歲以下成年人應該考慮接種阿斯利康疫苗以儘早取得保護的好處和風險。

你可以和你的醫生談談。

在病毒爆發期間感染 COVID-19 的風險很高時，接種疫苗會有更多好處。

謝謝。
 
如需更多資料，請瀏覽 health.gov.au

致電殘疾人士通道(Disability Gateway)求助熱線：1800 643 787 或

瀏覽殘疾人士通道網站：  www.disabilitygateway.gov.au

若您失聰或有聽力或語言障礙，您可以致電全國聾啞人士傳話服務 (National Relay Service)：133 677

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Simplified Chinese)
description:
In this video, with Simplified Chinese captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
大家好，我是Lucas de Toca医生。我是通过全科医生诊所推广疫苗接种计划的负责人。
 
鉴于目前COVID-19 Delta毒株的感染风险增加，我想向您介绍一下接种阿斯利康疫苗的最新动态。

如果距离您接种第一剂阿斯利康疫苗已过去了至少四周的时间，则应尽快安排第二剂疫苗接种。

该建议来自于澳大利亚免疫技术咨询小组（ATAGI）。

请注意，对于年满60岁的人来说，接种阿斯利康疫苗的好处大大超过了风险。

疫情期间，疫苗接种对于该群体来说至关重要。

由于辉瑞疫苗目前供应有限，60岁以下的成年人应考虑接种阿斯利康疫苗预先获得保护的相关好处和风险。

您可向医生咨询这个问题。

疫情期间，COVID-19的感染风险会很高，接种疫苗的好处也会更多。

感谢您的配合。
 
欲了解更多信息，请访问health.gov.au

请致电1800 643 787，联系Disability GatewayHelpline或

访问Disability Gateway网站  www.disabilitygateway.gov.au

如果您是失聪人士或有听力或语言障碍，请致电133 677 联系全国中继服务

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Bengali)
description:
In this video, with Bengali captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
হ্যালো, আমি ডঃ লুকাস ডি টোকা, এবং আমি জিপিদের মাধ্যমে ভ্যাকসিন কর্মসূচী পরিচালনায় নেতৃত্ব দিচ্ছি। 
এই মুহূর্তে কভিড ১৯ ডেল্টা ধরনটিতে মানুষের আক্রান্ত হওয়ার বর্ধিত ঝুঁকির প্রেক্ষাপটে আমি আপনাকে অ্যাস্ট্রাজেনিকা ভ্যাকসিন নেয়ার ব্যাপারে হালনাগাদ তথ্য দিতে চাই। 
 
আপনি যদি অন্তত ৪ সপ্তাহ আগে অ্যাস্ট্রাজেনিকা ভ্যাকসিনের প্রথম ডোজ নিয়ে থাকেন, তাহলে যত দ্রুত সম্ভব আপনি দ্বিতীয় ডোজটি নেয়ার ব্যবস্থা নিন। 

এই পরামর্শটি অস্ট্রেলিয়ান টেকনিকেল অ্যাডভাইসরি গ্রুপ ইন ইমিউনাইজেশন বা ATAGI থেকে এসেছে।   

মনে রাখবেন ৬০ কিংবা তদূর্ধ্ব লোকদের জন্য অ্যাস্ট্রাজেনিকা ভ্যাকসিন নেয়ার উপকারিতা এর ঝুঁকির চেয়ে অনেক বেশী।   

প্রাদুর্ভাবের সময়ে ভ্যাকসিন নেয়া এই গ্রুপের লোকদের জন্য জরুরী। 

যেহেতু এই মুহূর্তে ফাইজার ভ্যাকসিনের সরবরাহ কম, ৬০ বছরের কম বয়সী লোকদের অ্যাস্ট্রাজেনিকা ভ্যাকসিনের মাধ্যমে আগেভাগেই সুরক্ষিত থাকার উপকারিতা ও ঝুঁকি সম্পর্কে চিন্তা করা উচিত। 

আপনি এই ব্যাপারে আপনার ডাক্তারের সাথে কথা বলতে পারেন।  

প্রাদুর্ভাবের সময়ে যখন কভিড ১৯ এ আক্রান্ত হওয়ার ঝুঁকি বেশী থাকে তখন ভ্যাকসিন আপনাকে বাড়তি উপকারিতা প্রদান করতে পারে। 

আপনাকে ধন্যবাদ।  
 
আরও তথ্যের জন্য health.gov.au ওয়েবসাইটটি দেখুন। 

1800 643 787 নম্বরে ডিজঅ্যাবিলিটি গেটওয়ে হেল্পলাইনে যোগাযোগ করুন অথবা 

ডিজঅ্যাবিলিটি গেটওয়ের ওয়েবসাইট www.disabilitygateway.gov.au দেখুন। 
আপনি যদি বধির কিংবা বাক প্রতিবন্ধী হন তাহলে 133 677 নম্বরে ন্যাশনাল রিলে সার্ভিসে যোগাযোগ করতে পারেন।

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Assyrian)
description:
In this video, with Assyrian captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:
ܫܠܵܡܵܐ ܠܵܘܟܼܘܿܢ، ܐܵܢܵܐ ܝܼܘܸܢ ܐܵܣܝܵܐ ܠܘܼܟܵܣ ܕܝܼ ܬܘܿܟܵܐ، ܘܐܵܢܵܐ ܝܼܘܸܢ ܡܕܲܒܪܵܢܵܐ ܕܡܲܨܠܵܝܬܵܐ ܕܚܘܼܪܙܵܐ ܕܛܲܥܲܡܬܵܐ ܒܐܘܼܪܚܵܐ ܕܐܵܣܝܹ̈ܐ ܓܵܘܵܢܵܝܹ̈ܐ (GP's). 

ܒܥܹܐܠܝܼ ܕܡܲܕܸܥܸܢ ܗܘܵܐ ܠܵܘܟܼܘܿܢ ܒܘܼܬ ܡܵܘܕܥܵܢܘܼܬܵܐ ܒܘܼܫ ܚܲܕܲܬܬܵܐ ܒܘܼܬ ܛܘܼܥܵܡܵܐ ܕ AstraZeneca، ܟܲܕ ܒܸܙܝܵܕܵܐ ܝܠܹܗ ܩܸܢܛܵܐ ܕܐ݉ܢܵܫܹ̈ܐ ܕܛܵܦܝܼ ܒ COVID-19 Delta strain ܓܵܘ ܕܐܵܗܵܐ ܥܸܕܵܢܵܐ.      
 
ܐܸܢ ܫܩܝܼܠܹܐ ܝܬܘܿܢ ܠܣܸܪܦܵܘܟܼܘܿܢ ܩܲܕܡܵܝܵܐ ܕ AstraZeneca  ܒܵܨܘܿܪܵܐ ܒܵܨܘܿܪܵܐ ܡܼܢ ܩܵܕܡ ܐܲܪܒܥܵܐ ܫܵܒܼܘܿܥܹ̈ܐ، ܓܵܪܸܓ ܡܲܪܝܸܙܝܼܬܘܿܢ ܠܣܸܪܦܵܘܟܼܘܿܢ ܬܪܲܝܵܢܵܐ ܟܡܵܐ ܕܡܵܨܝܼܬܘܿܢ ܒܓ̰ܲܠܕܘܼܬܵܐ.    

ܢܲܨܝܼܗܲܬ ܐ݉ܬܹܐܠܵܗܿ ܡܼܢ ܣܝܼܥܬܵܐ ܡܲܠܘܿܟܼܬܵܐ ܐܘܿܣܬܪܵܠܝܵܝܬܵܐ ܬܸܩܢܝܼܩܵܝܬܵܐ (Australian Technical Advisory Group) ܒܘܼܬ ܡܚܲܣܢܵܢܘܼܬܵܐ ܝܲܢ ATAGI.

ܕܟܼܘܿܪܘܼܢ، ܩܵܐ ܐ݉ܢܵܫܹ̈ܐ ܕܥܘܼܡܪܲܝܗܝ ܝܼܠܹܗ 60 ܫܸܢܹ̈ܐ ܘܥܘܼܠܘܼܠ، ܦܵܝܕܵܐ ܕܛܲܥܲܡܬܵܐ ܒܛܘܼܥܵܡܵܐ ܕ AstraZeneca  ܪܵܒܵܐ ܒܘܼܫ ܨܦܵܝܝܼ ܝܠܵܗܿ ܡܼܢ ܩܸܢܛܹܗ.  

ܛܲܥܲܡܬܵܐ ܝܼܠܵܗܿ ܐܵܢܲܢܩܵܝܬܵܐ ܩܵܐ ܕܐܵܗܵܐ ܩܘܼܒܘܼܚܬܵܐ ܓܵܘ ܚܕܵܐ ܦܪܵܣܬܵܐ. 

ܣܲܒܵܒ ܡܙܲܘܲܕܬܵܐ ܕܛܘܼܥܵܡܵܐ ܕ Pfizer ܗܵܕܝܼܵܐ ܡܬܘܼܚܸܡܬܵܐ ܝܠܵܗܿ، ܐ݉ܢܵܫܹ̈ܐ ܟܡܝܼܠܹ̈ܐ ܒܫܸܢܹ̈ܐ ܬܚܘܿܬ 60 ܫܸܢܹ̈ܐ ܓܵܪܸܓ ܬܲܚܡܸܢܝܼ ܒܘܼܬ ܦܵܝܕܹ̈ܐ ܘܩܸܢܛܹ̈ܐ ܕܩܢܵܝܬܵܐ ܕܚܲܡܲܝܬܵܐ ܒܟܼܝܼܪܬܵܐ ܒܐܘܼܪܚܵܐ ܕܛܘܼܥܵܡܵܐ ܕ AstraZeneca.  

ܡܵܨܝܼܬܘܿܢ ܗܲܡܙܸܡܝܼܬܘܿܢ ܥܲܡ ܐܵܣܝܵܘܟܼܘܿܢ ܒܘܼܬ ܐܵܗܵܐ ܡܸܢܕܝܼ.

ܛܲܥܲܡܬܵܐ ܡܵܨܝܵܐ ܕܡܙܲܘܸܕܵܐ ܦܵܝܕܹ̈ܐ ܙܵܘܕܵܢܹ̈ܐ ܐܝܼܡܲܢ ܕܐܝܼܬ ܩܸܢܛܵܐ ܪܵܡܵܐ ܕܐ݉ܢܵܫܹ̈ܐ ܛܵܦܝܼ ܒ COVID-19 ܓܵܘ ܚܕܵܐ ܦܪܵܣܬܵܐ.  

ܗܵܘܝܼܬܘܿܢ ܒܲܣܝܼܡܹ̈ܐ. 

ܩܵܐ ܡܵܘܕܥܵܢܘܼܬܵܐ ܙܵܘܕܵܢܬܵܐ، ܣܲܚܒܸܪܘܼܢ  health.gov.au   

ܡܲܚܒܸܪܘܼܢ ܩܵܐ ܚܘܼܛܵܐ ܕܗܲܝܲܪܬܵܐ ܕܫܲܦܠܘܼܬܵܐ (Disability Gateway Helpline) ܥܲܠ ܡܸܢܝܵܢܵܐ 1800 643 787 ܝܲܢ 

ܣܲܚܒܸܪܘܼܢ ܠܫܵܘܦܵܐ ܐܸܠܸܟܬܪܘܿܢܵܝܵܐ ܕܫܲܦܠܘܼܬܵܐ ܕ Gateway ܥܲܠ   www.disabilitygateway.gov.au

ܐܸܢ ܝܼܬܘܿܢ ܟܲܪܹ̈ܐ ܝܲܢ ܐܝܼܬܠܵܘܟܼܘܿܢ ܙܲܒܘܼܢܘܼܬܵܐ ܕܫܡܸܥܬܵܐ ܝܲܢ ܕܗܲܡܙܲܡܬܵܐ، ܡܵܨܝܼܬܘܿܢ ܡܲܚܒܸܪܝܼܬܘܿܢ ܩܵܐ ܚܸܠܡܲܬ ܕܫܲܢܲܝܬܵܐ ܐܘܼܡܬܵܝܬܵܐ ܥܲܠ ܡܸܢܝܵܢܵܐ 133 677

title: Dr Lucas de Toca explains why COVID-19 vaccines are important in an outbreak (Arabic)
description:
In this video, with Arabic captions, Dr Lucas de Toca explains the importance of COVID-19 vaccines in an outbreak setting.

Transcript:

مرحباً، 
أنا الطبيب لوكاس دي توكا، وأقود برنامج طرح اللقاح من خلال ممارسي الطب العام.
 
أردت أن أطلعكم على آخر المستجدات بشأن استخدام لقاح AstraZeneca ، نظراً لزيادة خطر إصابة الأشخاص بسلالة دلتا COVID-19  في الوقت الراهن.

إذا كنت قد تلقيت جرعتك الأولى من AstraZeneca منذ أربعة أسابيع على الأقل،  يجب عليك  الترتيب لتلقي الجرعة الثانية بأسرع وقت ممكن.

وردت هذه النصيحة من المجموعة الاستشارية الفنية الأسترالية المعنية بالتحصين أو  .ATAGI

تذكر، أن الأشخاص الذين تزيد أعمارهم عن 60 عاماً، تفوق فوائد التطعيم بلقاح AstraZeneca  المخاطر بشدة.

التطعيم ضروري لهذه المجموعة في حالة تفشي المرض.

ونظراً لأن الامدادات بلقاح Pfizer محدودة في الوقت الحالي، يجب على البالغين الذين تقل أعمارهم عن 60 عاماً التفكير في الفوائد و مخاطر تلقي حماية مبكرة من خلال لقاح  .AstraZeneca 

يمكنك التحدث مع طبيبك عن هذا الموضوع.

يمكن أن يوفر التطعيم فوائد متزايدة عندما يكون هناك خطر كبير من إصابة الناس بـ COVID-19 عند تفشي المرض.

شكرا لكم.
 
للمزيد من المعلومات،  الرجاء زيارة  health.gov.au  

اتصلوا  بخط  المساعدة Disability Gateway على 787 643 1800  أو

قوموا بزيارة موقع disability Gateway على  www.disabilitygateway.gov.au 

إذا كنت أصمّاً أو تعاني من ضعف في السمع أو النطق،  يمكنك الاتصال بخدمة البدّالة الوطنية على  677 133

title: Dr Marilyn Clarke explains how vaccines work, and why pregnant women should get the COVID-19 vaccine
description:
In this video, Worimi woman, obstetrician and gynaecologist Dr Marilyn Clarke describes how COVID-19 vaccines work, and explains why it’s important for pregnant women to get the COVID-19 vaccine.

Transcript:

The COVID-19 vaccination advice for pregnant women has recently changed.

Because pregnant women are at a higher risk of severe disease from COVID-19, it's recommended that they are offered the Pfizer vaccine at any stage of their pregnancy. COVID-19 vaccines train your body to develop an immune response, teaching it how to fight the virus, ensuring you don't get seriously sick from COVID-19.

The latest information shows that the vaccine may offer some protection
for your baby as well. If you're breastfeeding, you can receive a COVID-19 vaccination at any time, and you don't need to stop breastfeeding after vaccination.

If you have any questions, either about the vaccine when you're pregnant
or if you're trying to fall pregnant, talk to your local healthcare worker or visit health.gov.au.

title: AFL legend Adam Goodes gets his COVID-19 vaccine
description:
Watch Adnyamathanha and Narungga man Adam Goodes explain why he chose to get the COVID-19 vaccine and the importance of understanding the risks of COVID-19, and the benefits of vaccination.

Transcript:
Having my first injection today does give me a peace of mind that I am doing my part and helping our families and our communities.

To be honest, I have put a lot of thought into getting the COVID vaccination. My obstetrician told us that my wife was able to get vaccinated to protect her and our baby. That made it very clear to me that is was very safe and it’s something that not only I, but all of us should really have a think about. Understand the risks involved in contracting COVID-19.

I think it’s very important that all of us here in Australia should get vaccinated to protect our family and friends. To my Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander brothers and sisters, it’s just as important for us to know the risks of COVID-19. But more importantly, the benefits of being vaccinated and the benefits to our mob and all of us going out there and getting that jab.

Now that I’ve had my first injection, being vaccinated, it’s definitely something that I feel really proud about, not only to help protect myself and my family, but for me to do my part. By getting vaccinated, it’s helping us all move closer to getting back to normality. 

I'm arming myself against COVID-19 to protect myself, my family and the community.

title: The National Aged Care Mandatory Quality Indicator Program (QI Program) Webinar
description:
From 1 July 2021, the National Aged Care Mandatory Quality Indicator Program (QI Program) requires approved providers of residential aged care to report on new quality indicators across five crucial clinical areas.
QI Program data must be reported quarterly and according to the requirements in the QI Program Manual 2.0 – Part A
The webinar will help you to understand the new quality indicators and meet changed QI Program requirements from 1 July 2021, by covering:
• quality indicator definitions 
• collection and reporting requirements 
• guidance materials
• questions and answers

title: Don’t fool around with syphilis
description:
This video provides information on the current outbreak of syphilis happening across Australia and how you can protect youself and your partner from getting the sexually transmissible infection. 

Transcript:
You might have heard of the sexually transmissible infection called syphilis, but what you might not know is that there’s currently a syphilis outbreak across Australia. 
Men who have sex with men, women of childbearing age, and those living in known outbreak areas are most at risk, including affected Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities.
Syphilis is a disease caused by a bacteria and it is totally treatable. In fact, with early diagnosis, most people can be completely cured. But we also need to remember it’s a serious disease and over time can cause sores and ulcers, rashes, skin lesions, swollen lymph glands, hair loss, muscle and joint aches, headaches, and fatigue. 
And if left untreated, can eventually cause brain infections, dementia, lung and heart failure, blindness and even death. 
So how can we stop the rise of syphilis? The best way is to practise safe sex. Use condoms and dental dams, avoid sex if you feel unwell or show symptoms, and get tested regularly. 
Remember, people don’t always get symptoms so they don’t always know they have it, which means even regular partners need regular syphilis tests. And if you’re pregnant, early testing is extra important to ensure you don’t pass syphilis onto your baby. 
So stay safe, get tested, and have regular health checks.
And don’t fool around with syphilis.

title: James’ vaccination experience
description:
In this video, James Manders, who has visual impairment, shares his experience getting his COVID-19 vaccination.

Full Transcript:

How did you feel about getting your COVID-19 vaccination?
I was excited because we’ve got something that can help stop the transmission of this virus, which has affected us all. So I was really looking forward to it.
Why is it so important for Australians to get vaccinated?
Part of my day job is to travel, and I like to get out and about. When we have shutdown or lockdown restrictions, it’s not good for people’s wellbeing. So we need to build our herd immunity in our communities so that getting the vaccination will help us to get out and do what we do best.
What did you do to prepare for your vaccination appointment?
I followed the guidance of our TGA because in my line of work I connect with them and they’re world-class. So if they say it’s safe and they approve it then for me it’s just like a flu vaccine.
Where did you get your vaccination?
I got my vaccine at the ACT health vaccination hub in Garran. It was easy - walk in, sit down, I was out within half an hour. It was very easy.
Have you experienced any side effects?
No side effects. Just like any other vaccination that you get, the flu vaccines or any other regular vaccination program. It’s just a little bit of a sore arm, but no problem at all.
Have you received your second vaccine dose yet?
All done. I had it last night, and again no issues, I feel fine. Again, now I can focus on booking up my travel schedule to get out and about to do what I need to do for my work.
Were you hesitant before getting the vaccine?
I trust the authorities and the health regulator to make sure it’s safe. Like anything, there’s going to be the odd side effect but this is absolutely no problem at all.
What message do you have for Australians that haven’t booked in to get their vaccine?
Do it as quickly as you can. People who don’t get the vaccination I think will just delay us returning to a normal life.

title: Elsie from Thursday Island says it’s a no brainer to get the COVID-19 vaccine
description:
Elsie Seriat, proud mum, runner, and graduate from the Indigenous Marathon Foundation, explains how important it is to protect yourself against COVID-19 by getting the vaccine when you can.

Transcript:
I got the COVID-19 vaccine because I believe that’s its important for myself, and also to keep my community and my family safe.

My name is Elsie, born and bred on Thursday Island.

I’m a proud mum, a deadly runner, a graduate from the Indigenous Marathon Foundation.

I work for the Johnathan Thurston Academy as a JTBelieve Officer and also a community researcher for the Mayi Kuwaya Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Wellbeing Study.

Being a frequent flyer, having to travel around the country a lot, it was a no-brainer for me to get the vaccination.

I was also excited because the vaccination team is here on Thursday Island and is doing their rollout.

And my mum is getting her vaccine done, which I think is really awesome.

I want to encourage everyone, especially the young people in the community that if the vaccination team is around, go down and get vaccinated.

It will keep yourself safe and your family safe.

To find out more information, go have a yarn with your health worker or visit health.gov.au

title: Getting your COVID-19 vaccine - animation for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples
description:
This animation is for healthcare workers to support them explaining what the COVID-19 vaccination process will look like and what to expect during and after the vaccine.

Transcript:
We have heard about the COVID-19 sickness and how lots of people around the world and in Australia have gotten very sick and died from the disease.

We have been lucky in Australia but as travel and tourism starts we need to protect our elders and future generations.

There are new vaccines which will teach your body how to fight the COVID 19 sickness, the vaccines will protect you, your family and your community from getting really sick from COVID-19.

You don’t have to have the vaccine but it is strongly recommended.

Make sure you get the vaccine when it is your turn.

There are different types of the COVID-19 vaccine and you’ll need to have two doses of the same.

Before you get vaccinated, the clinic will ask you some Health questions.

First they will ask if you have any allergies. An allergy is when you come close to something and get sick very quickly.

You might get an itchy rash. Your tongue may get big. You might breath fast or cough a lot.

Other questions you’ll get asked are about the medicines you take.

If you have a weak immune system, if you are pregnant or breast feeding.

If you have a bleeding disorder. If you take medicine to thin your blood and if you have been sick recently.

The clinic will also ask your name and date of birth as well, and who your closest family members are.

They will ask you if you understand all the information they have talked to you about and if you agree to get the vaccine you’ll have to sign a consent form to get the vaccine.

To be vaccinated you will need to get a needle in your arm. You’ll need two needles on different days to be fully vaccinated against COVID-19.

Once you get the needle the clinic nurse will get you to stay at the clinic for 15 minutes to make sure you are okay.

After you get the vaccine you might get some mild side effects such as a sore arm, a headache, feeling tired or having a fever.

This should only last 1-2 days it is normal and means the vaccine is working,
If you have severe symptoms like a headache that just wont go away, are worried about how you are feeling or have any questions, make sure you talk to the health clinics.

It is really important to get two COVID vaccine needles to get the best protection.

Its okay to get the needles at different places, like another community or location.

Your vaccine will be recorded on the national register, your health clinic can look up your vaccination history for you and give you a certificate once you have received two needles.

To find out more have a yarn with your local healthcare worker or your doctor.

title: Dr Lucas de Toca provides an update on AstraZeneca age recommendations to people with disability
description:
Dr Lucas de Toca summarises the new information and recommendations on AstraZeneca announced on 17 June 2021.

Full Transcript:

Hi, I’m Dr Lucas de Toca, and I lead the rollout of the vaccination program through GPs.
I wanted to give you an update on the vaccine rollout, as the age recommendation for the vaccines has changed. 
Our immunisation experts have said that the Pfizer vaccine is preferred for adults aged under 60.
This means that if you are under 60 years of age, you should get the Pfizer vaccine.
The update came after new evidence showed a higher risk of the rare blood clotting condition, thrombosis with thrombocytopenia syndrome, or TTS, in people aged 50 to 59. 
If you are 60 years and over, it’s important to understand that the benefits of vaccination against COVID-19 outweigh the risks of TTS. The AstraZeneca vaccine is still very good at protecting you from getting very sick or dying from COVID-19.
People who have had their first dose of the AstraZeneca COVID-19 vaccine without any serious side effects should still receive their second dose.
This includes adults under 60 years of age. 
Having your second dose offers you the best protection from getting seriously sick from COVID-19. If you’ve had your first dose, I encourage you to book in for your second dose of the same vaccine. 
Many millions of people around the world have had their vaccines safely. The vaccines are still our most important way to prevent serious illness or death from COVID-19. 
Thank you.
For more information:
Visit health.gov.au. 
Call the Disability Gateway Helpline on 1800 643 787 or visit the Disability Gateway website on www.disabilitygateway.gov.au
If you are deaf, or have a hearing or speech impairment, you can call the National Relay Service on 133 677.
As of 29 June 2021, eligibility for the AstraZeneca vaccine has been expanded. 
For more information, visit health.gov.au/covid-19-vaccines

title: Ella Kris wants her Thursday Island mob protected from COVID-19
description:
Ella Kris, Chairperson for Torres and Cape Hospital and Health Service Board, explains how important it is to protect yourself against COVID-19 by getting the vaccine when you can.

Transcript:
Getting the COVID-19 vaccine is the best protection against getting the virus.

My name is Ella Kris, I am the chairperson for the Torres and Cape Hospital and Health Service Board.

Up in the Torres and Cape, we haven’t had COVID-19.

But once we start, people start travelling in and out – we cant guarantee.

And by protecting ourselves, we’re protecting our community, protecting the Elders, we’re protecting where we live and protecting our culture.

It was really important that I got the vaccine, as the Chair of Torres and Cape.

I have to show people that it’s the right thing and its safe.

Remember, it is important to get two doses.

Pfizer is 21 days apart and AstraZeneca is 3 months apart.

When the vaccination team comes to your community, its really important to go and get vaccinated.

For more information, just talk to your local health worker.

title: How to do the test – Indigenous bowel screening
description:
This video for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people explains how to do the bowel cancer screening test. The test is part of the National Bowel Cancer Screening Program.

Transcript:

The national bowel cancer screening kit contains:
• 2 toilet liners (these liners are put into the toilet with the writing facing up to catch the poo)
• 2 collection tubes
• 1 ziplock bag
• a reply paid envelope, and
• instructions on how to do the test.

How to do the test.

Step 1 – Prepare
On one of the tube labels, write your
• full name
• date of birth
• date you take the sample.

Before collecting your sample, do a wee and flush the toilet.
Put the toilet liner over the water in the toilet bowl. The writing should be facing up.
If the toilet liner sinks, it’s still ok to take the sample, or you can request a new kit.

Step 2 – Collect
Do your poo onto the toilet liner.
Open the collection tube by twisting the green cap.
Scrape the tip of the stick over different areas of the surface of the poo. The sample only needs to be tiny – smaller than a grain of rice.
Put the stick back into the collection tube and click the lid shut.
Shake the tube up and down several times. Do not remove the stick again.
Flush the toilet liner and poo down the toilet.
Wash your hands.

Step 3 – Store and repeat
Place the tube into the ziplock bag.
Put the sample in the fridge. Do not freeze.

Repeat steps 1 to 3 with the second collection tube when you do another poo (on the same day, the next day, or as soon as possible).

Step 4 – Send
Complete the Participant Details form.
Write your name and address on the back of the Reply Paid envelope and sign the front.
Put the Participant Details form and the 2 collection tubes (in the sealed ziplock bag) into the Reply Paid envelope and seal it.
Take the envelope to a post office within 24 hours, or mail in the late afternoon (before 6pm) using an Australia Post mailbox.
The samples must remain cool, so do not leave them in a hot place such as a car.

title: 5 reasons people are getting the COVID-19 vaccine #IDIF
description:
In this video we visit the Northern Vaccination Centre/North Eastern Respiratory Clinic in South Australia to ask people why they’re getting vaccinated for COVID-19 and who they’re doing it for. 
Find out their reasons and share your own on social media using #IDAF (I did it for).

Transcript:
I did it for myself, because
I don't wanna get COVID.

I did it for my
family, my grandchildren.

I did it for prevention

and not to spread the
disease in to community.

I did it for my friends
and work colleagues.

I did it for myself to be safe

and I also did it to keep
my grandchildren safe.

I did it because it's recommended

because we're in a pandemic,

and I'm gonna do everything
I can not to get COVID.

- The more people are vaccinated,

the better it's gonna be, I think.

I recommend it.

There's no inconvenience, it's easy.

I think everyone should have a vaccine.

title: Care for Kids’ Ears – Strong hearing, strong start video
description:
The Care for Kids’ Ears – Strong hearing, strong start video shows teachers, parents and health care workers talk about the importance of ear health and getting regular ear checks.

Transcript:
Muffled sound of children talking and playing
This is what the world sounds like to a child with hearing loss from ear disease
Kim – health worker: I think about my nieces and nephews and the dramas that they go through just ‘cause they can’t hear. And it makes… it makes it even harder because I want, I want the best for my mob and my community.
Ear disease is serious and can cause loss of hearing forever
Alan – health worker: Ear disease is a whole spectrum of problems anything from a simple temporary impairment or infection all the way to deafness.
Ear disease can be prevented and treated
Chantelle – Parent: Any discharge, any of the signs of kids, you know, rubbing at their ear, crying, usually rubbing at their ear, especially when they’re babies, when they rub at their ear you can tell.
Cellia – Health Worker: They get the snuffles and then the sore throat and then the ears tend to get infected inside.
Ear infections can lead to ear disease
Pam – Teacher: I know it’s hard as parents ‘cause sometimes there are no symptoms that you know that your child has problems with their ears so it is really, really important that you take your child to the doctor regularly to make sure they get their ears checked.
Pam – Teacher: Ear disease is preventable, but it’s really important that it’s detected early.
Alan – Health Worker: Well prevention is: don’t smoke around children, make sure you wash your hands, have healthy food and never poke your cotton buds down your ears.
Don’t stick anything in your kids’ ear
Kim – Health Worker: If a child’s ears perforate over time, again and again, that they actually end up with a certain percentage of hearing loss.
Pam – Teacher: If I’ve got students in the class and they can’t hear it makes it really hard to try and get them to participate in activities, talk to other kids, also, listen to what I’m saying, ‘cause most of the time I’m doing the talking so if they can’t hear me they’re just sitting there wondering what’s going on.
Chantelle – Parent: Well hearing is one of the most important senses.
Lenard – Parent: It’s important to have regular checks for your kids because, like, if they lose their hearing it makes communicating harder and talking and even understanding - it makes life a lot harder for them if they can’t hear.
Alan – Health Worker: Every time they come to the doctor, they should get their ears checked.
Latisha – Doctor: Don’t be ashamed to ask your doctor or your health professional or the registered nurse to have a look at your child’s ears because you can potentially change their life and have healthy, healthy children that grow up to be strong, deadly Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander adults.
Get your kids’ ears checked regularly
Strong hearing, strong start
Muffled sound of children talking and playing
www.careforkidsears.health.gov.au

title: Care for Kids’ Ears talking book
description:
The Care for Kids’ Ears – Strong hearing, strong start talking book explains the importance of ear health and getting regular ear checks.

Transcript:
This information is about keeping kids’ ears healthy. 
Ear disease is serious. It can lead to loss of hearing forever. 
Kids are not born with ear infections, but they can get an ear infection soon after birth. 
Kids might have ear disease if they: 
- have a cold (runny nose, coughing, sore throat)
- pain or fever
- runny fluid or pus from their ear.
Get your kids’ ear checked if they: 
- are pulling at their ears
- can’t hear you properly
- have diarrhoea or vomiting
- or aren’t eating.
Even if kids have no symptoms, you should get their ears checked regularly. 
Ear disease can be prevented and treated.
Do: 
- get ears checked
- wash hands and faces
- blow nose and put tissues in the bin
- and eat healthy food.
Don’t:
- smoke around kids
- put anything in kids’ ears.
With healthy ears kids can:
- learn language
- talk
- read
- and listen.
Keep kids’ ears healthy by getting them checked regularly by a health worker, nurse or doctor and following their advice about treatments. 
To find out more, go to www.careforkidsears.health.gov.au 
This is an Australian Government initiative.

title: Veronica Leaney lost her husband to COVID-19
description:
This video is of Veronica Leaney (and her daughter Cheryl) talking about the loss of her husband to COVID-19. In this video, Cheryl receives her second COVID vaccination. 

Transcript 

I'm still in denial. It's been nearly 18 months since Roger died. I really miss his companionship. I miss him there to talk to. It's just sad.

My name is Veronica Leaney. I'm 73 years old and I was married to my
husband for 52 years. And he died last year from COVID-19.

Today, I'm going down to the Wayville vaccination clinic with Cheryl, my younger daughter. And she's going to have
her second vaccination against COVID.

It will be good to know that my family is protected.
Roger was a reasonably fit man for a man of 74. He would go to the gym
three mornings a week.
He played golf every Tuesday.
I really thought he would be going to the hospital and he would come home and he would be fine.

Roger was in a COVID ward for about four days. And I was chatting to him on the phone and he said, "I'll have to hang up because they're bringing in the machine to test my breathing." And he said, "It's very noisy." So I will ring you afterwards and I never heard from him again.
His organs had totally failed.

It's so much easier to be vaccinated than to go through this heartbreak and loss. 
After having the virus myself, along with my husband having it, there was no question I wasn't going to have the vaccine.

You may feel a little off color the next day, a bit tired.

You might have a little bit of a sore muscle in your arm.

That's nothing compared to the virus.

We, as citizens, have to take on the responsibility of looking after ourselves  and our loved ones and our local community by being vaccinated.

title: Uncle Dale and Dale-Andrew talk about the COVID-19 vaccine
description:
This video shows Uncle Dale and Dale-Andrew fishing by the river, talking about the COVID-19 vaccine. This video is produced for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander audiences.

Transcript:
Dale Senior: Dale-Andrew, just to let you know, I went for my COVID vaccination the other day.

Dale-Andrew: Oh true. That's good, Dad. That's real good. I'm glad you've done that. And you are right? 

Dale Senior: Yeah, not too bad.

Dale-Andrew: That's good, that's good. What about all the other Uncles and Aunties, are they going to have it done too? 

Dale Senior: I'll give them a call and recommend they should do it. 

Dale-Andrew: You want to make sure, Dad. They listen to you. I was thinking about it the other night, we want you around as long as we can Dad, you know, for your grandchildren. 

Dale Senior: Yeah, I want to be around, as long as possible. You know, physically possible.  

Dale-Andrew: Because you’ve got a lot to teach them on family history and our traditions. 
That's why it's important about the elders getting this COVID vaccination. 

Dale Senior: Yeah, I'm glad I've done it too.

Dale-Andrew: Oh well, if you're brave enough to do it, I'll get mine done too then hey?

title: Aunty Val and Lelani talk about COVID-19 vaccines
description:
This video shows Aunty Val and Lelani sharing a cup of tea, talking about the COVID-19 vaccine. This video is produced for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander audiences.

Transcript:
Lelani: Mum, here's your cup of tea. 

Aunty Val : Thank you. 

Lelani: There you go. Beautiful. I've been talking to Auntie Jake. 

Aunty Val: Yes?

Lelani: And she's going to have the COVID-19 needle.

Aunty Val: Oh, great.

Lelani: And you're going to have it, aye? 

Aunty Val: Yes I think so. 

Lelani: So it'd be deadly if you go together aye?  

Aunty Val: We've always been together so yes, brings us closer. 

Lelani: So I'll arrange for you to go and have the needle together. It’s very important that our elders are still here to hand down the culture, the song and the dance for generations and generations after you. Which your granny handed all down that knowledge to you, didn't she Mum.

Aunty Val: Yeah, whatever we know about culture she taught us.

Lelani: But know what I think I'm going to have my COVID-19 needle too, so I can be around too to hear all those deadly stories from you and Auntie Jake.

title: COVID-19 vaccines – Explainer video on TTS
description:
This video explains what TTS is, and who is eligible to receive the AstraZeneca vaccine.

Transcript:
The vaccines currently used in Australia have been rigorously tested for safety and are highly effective.

A very rare but serious new side effect has emerged with the AstraZeneca vaccine - a blood clotting syndrome called thrombosis in combination with thrombocytopenia, or TTS.

TTS is extremely rare.
It’s also new, and was not found in the clinical trials for the AstraZeneca vaccine. 
Evidence shows that TTS is less likely in older adults.
And they have a higher risk of getting very sick if they get COVID-19
That is why the vaccine preferred for you has changed,
Depending on your age.
COVID-19 can spread quickly and widely and has resulted in the deaths of millions of people worldwide.

Vaccination is the most effective way to protect ourselves and our community against COVID-19.

To learn more visit health.gov.au

title: COVID-19 vaccination – Video – How COVID-19 vaccines work
description:
In this video, Doctor Sakshi explains how COVID-19 vaccines work.

Transcript: 
Hi, my name is Dr Sakshi and I’m a doctor. 

I am going to explain how COVID-19 vaccines work.

Vaccines are injected into your body. They do not remove anything from your body and they do not change your genes or DNA. 

COVID-19 vaccines teach your body to recognise and fight the COVID-19 virus. They do not contain COVID-19, and you cannot get COVID-19 from having the vaccines.

Mild side effects, like headaches or muscle pain, mean the vaccine is working. 

COVID-19 vaccines help prevent serious illness and death. Everyone can do their part to protect their family and community by getting vaccinated.

For more information on the COVID-19 vaccines visit health.gov.au/covid19-vaccines or call the National Coronavirus Helpline on 1800 020 080. For translating and interpreting services call 131 450.
